question_list.author: Celia Warren
question_list.text:
Oh, don't throw your toys out your pram!
Yes, I treat all your emails as spam.
Hurt your feelings? Don't care;
I don't like you, so there!
Just accept that I don't give a damn!
question_list.question: Why do I treat all your emails as spam?
alternate_answers:
Because I don't like you, so there!
Your feelings? I don't really care.
Just accept that I'm cold,
And your messages, old,
Are as welcome as a grizzly bear.

question_list.author: SheilaB
question_list.text:
Uncle Wayne always gives me a pain.
His ideas are vain and inane.
He's both asinine (fatuous)
And a gas bag who's flatuous.
I treat the old fool with disdain.
question_list.question: What is wrong with Uncle Wayne's ideas?
question_list.answer: Uncle Wayne's ideas are vain and inane.
alternate_answers:
Uncle Wayne's ideas are considered vain and inane,
He's both asinine and flatuous, causing disdain.

Based on the limerick, there are a few things wrong with Uncle Wayne's ideas:

1. They are described as "vain and inane" - meaning they are empty, worthless, and foolish.

2. He is characterized as being "asinine" - which means stupid or foolish. 

3. He is also described as being a "gas bag" who is "flatuous" - implying his ideas are full of hot air and empty rhetoric.

4. The narrator treats Uncle Wayne with "disdain" - showing a strong dislike and lack of respect for his ideas.

Overall, the limerick portrays Uncle Wayne's ideas as being foolish, stupid, and unworthy of serious consideration. The narrator clearly has a very negative view of his uncle's thought processes and opinions.

question_list.author: Joanna Keene
question_list.text:
Joey fingered Big Lou as the one
Who shot Johnny six times with his gun.
Snitched him out: "Louie did it;
The goon never hid it."
Now Joey lives life on the run.
question_list.question: Who did Joey finger for shooting Johnny?

question_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
question_list.text:
Our most serious faces we don
As the blamestorming session goes on.
Someone died. Who's to blame?
The one person we name
Is a janitor's helper named Juan.
question_list.question: Who do they blame in the blamestorming session after someone dies?
alternate_answers:
Based on the limericks, it seems the person they blame in the blamestorming session after someone dies is often a scapegoat or someone undeserving of the blame. 

For example, one limerick mentions:

"Someone died. Who's to blame?
The one person we name
Is a janitor's helper named Juan."

This suggests that in the blamestorming session, they unfairly blame an innocent person, like the janitor's helper Juan, rather than finding the true cause of the death.

question_list.author: MikeAq
question_list.text:
To compose a morose epicedium
Can brighten one's torpor and tedium.
I myself have an urge
To create a sad dirge —
One not overly mournful, just medium.
question_list.question: How can one brighten one's torpor and tedium?
alternate_answers:
The limerick suggests that composing a morose epicedium (a funeral song or poem) can help brighten one's torpor and tedium. The limerick states:

"To compose a morose epicedium 
Can brighten one's torpor and tedium.
I myself have an urge
To create a sad dirge —
One not overly mournful, just medium."

So the answer is that writing a moderately melancholy funeral poem or song can help alleviate boredom and listlessness, according to the limerick.

Compose a morose epicedium.
Craft a sad dirge, not too mournful,
Just medium, not scornful,
To lift your spirits, a musical medium.

question_list.author: Howard Spindel
question_list.text:
I've a tree in my yard in a plight;
All its leaves are diseased — it's a sight.
And the skin of that tree
Peels to such a degree
That its bark is much worse than its blight.
question_list.question: What is the plight of the tree in my yard?
alternate_answers: The tree in the yard has diseased leaves and peeling bark, which is a sight.

question_list.author: proof
question_list.text:
Have a car and my clothes without fail
Outside of this old county jail.
It has only one fence,
 Which does not make much sense,
So tomorrow I'll scale it and bail.
question_list.question: what about the county jail does not make much sense?
alternate_answers: The limerick about the county jail mentions a person who plans to scale the fence to escape the jail, which is not a typical or sensible way to leave a jail.

Based on the limerick, the detail that does not make much sense about the county jail is that it "has only one fence". The limerick suggests this is odd, implying a typical county jail would have more than one fence to help secure the facility and prevent inmates from escaping.

question_list.author: MikeAq
question_list.text:
Mr. Thistle, what's this all about?
All our rules you dismiss — baldly flout.
I have read your epistle;
It made my hairs bristle.
I'm blowing the whistle — you're out!
question_list.question: Does Mr. Thistle follow our rules?
alternate_answers: Mr. Thistle does not follow the rules consistently. He often disregards them without explanation or justification.

Based on the limericks provided, the question appears to be about the limerick that mentions "Mr. Thistle". The relevant limerick is:

"Mr. Thistle, what's this all about? 
All our rules you dismiss — baldly flout.
I have read your epistle;
It made my hairs bristle.
I'm blowing the whistle — you're out!"

This limerick suggests that Mr. Thistle does not follow the rules, as the speaker is blowing the whistle on him for dismissing and flouting the rules.

question_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
question_list.text:
That damn call button jockey, room 9,
Is a pain in the base of my spine.
For no reason he rings
About minuscule things.
His sole purpose? To hear himself whine.
question_list.question: What is the sole purpose of the occupant of room 9?
alternate_answers: The sole purpose of the occupant of room 9 is to repeatedly press the call button, which can be quite frustrating for others.
The sole purpose of the occupant of room 9 is to ring the call button for no significant reason, mainly to hear himself whine.

question_list.author: Richard English
question_list.text:
Some folks might think cranberry glass
Is for fruit of the cranberry class.
But it's glass of deep red,
With a gold sheen, and said
To be sought by the English top brass.
question_list.question: What is sought by the English top brass?

limerick_list.author: Kevin
limerick_list.text:
Ambidextrous, yes, that's what I am
At tennis and badminton—wham!
I can smash day and night
With my left and my right.
My opponents despair, hissing "Damn!"

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
The genie is out of the bottle.
Societal ills are full-throttle.
With mass devastation,
The next generation
Will have to come in and remodel.

limerick_list.author: David
limerick_list.text:
When his friends call him backward, Jon sneers:
"I am very advanced in some spheres.
With my jigsaw techniques,
I can do in six weeks
Puzzles clearly marked '2-4 years'."

limerick_list.author: Howard Spindel
limerick_list.text:
That show on TV makes me bridle
My rage (to degrees homicidal!).
I'm checking my urges
To murder those scourges —
The slothful American Idle.

limerick_list.author: Workshop
limerick_list.text:
Daily life? Mine begins after nine
So that breakfast and lunch can combine.
Then I take a short nap,
Read some innocent crap
And watch telly. My life is divine.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Laryngitis gripped me and my kin,
So I called at the home of Doc Quinn.
To his wife, I croaked, "Faye,
Is the doc in today?"
"He's asleep," she replied, "C'mon in."

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
With each house on my block a Cape Cod,
My new Gothic revival looked odd.
I broke ranks with their style,
Raising everyone's bile:
"We will burn down this eyesore, by God!"

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
"My transmission goes 'Wheee! Klonck-klonck! Wheee!'"
The mechanic just marks "CND."
"What's the source? Are you deaf?"
He jots down "CNF,"
And then hands me my bill and my key.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
That defender came in high and hard,
So he's booked; the ref's shown him a card.
Such tackles are banned,
Lest things get out of hand.
Once more? On the spot the guy's barred.

limerick_list.author: Andrew Burnet
limerick_list.text:
My great masterpiece—one that I prized—
Was rewritten, restyled and revised,
And at terrible cost—
The original's lost!
Hence my chagrin may well be surmised.

limerick_list.author: Carol June Hooker
limerick_list.text:
On November the second, we'd pray
As All Souls' Day mass Father would say.
Deacons named each dead soul,
And for each, bells would toll
As the incense uplifted away.

limerick_list.author: JimInRoses
limerick_list.text:
An air-line, when used for a dare,
Can cause injuries painful to bear,
For air, when compressed,
Makes your innards distressed,
And does damage to — Heaven knows where.

limerick_list.author: speedysnail
limerick_list.text:
The alopex lives near the pole,
Where he feeds on the marmot and vole,
And wears socks on his feet
In his wintry retreat:
A cosy Alaskan fox-hole.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
I was stabbed through the heart by an ackman
While sailing with actor Gene Hackman.
This maritime thug
Then opined with a shrug:
"Hell, you shoulda stayed home and played Pac-Man!"

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Hunt the gavial? That crocodilian,
Found in India, isn't Brazilian.
You're in Rio, so you,
'Less you visit the zoo,
Have a chance of but one in a million.

limerick_list.author: rusty
limerick_list.text:
Though banged up in his dark prison cell,
Jack's dressed up to the nines.  He looks swell,
And bang-up to the mark
Like a flash office clerk.
(Tomorrow, he'll hang.  Toll the bell.)

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
Johnny Ace, after singing a set,
Was backstage playing Russian roulette.
That's a game he would lose.
Fans were left with the blues,
And they're pledging their love for him yet.

limerick_list.author: John Ramos
limerick_list.text:
My spirit's at peace; I'm content.
I believe that my life's been well-spent.
I've got eupathy, dude:
A good, right-feeling mood.
I'm a happy, agreeable gent.

limerick_list.author: John Young
limerick_list.text:
"I've just ordered a spectre detector",
Boasted Hector, our gullible rector,
"Ghouls are cold, so I'm told,
And a silvery-gold—
One suspects they reflect like electre."

limerick_list.author: Mark Mironer
limerick_list.text:
"We refuse to serve ropes in this spot!"
But a clever young cord hatched a plot.
So he got himself tangled;
His cut end he mangled.
"Hey, aren't you that rope?" "Afraid not!"

limerick_list.author: Carol June Hooker
limerick_list.text:
When Albula (or bonefish) scales shimmer
And a breeze sets the water a-glimmer,
In the mangrove lagoons
They hide out from raccoons
And the equally hungry black skimmer.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
Try this drinking game, folks: fuzzy duck.
Say those words taking turns.  Don't get stuck
When a buddy says Does he? —
Avoid replies scuzzy:
Return "ducky fuzz".  Yeah,  good  luck!

limerick_list.author: Sussexdownsman
limerick_list.text:
At Dogdyke and Chester-le-Street
Sleepers sleep; there's no cat on a seat
Where passengers waited.
The branch lines were fated
By Beeching's plan, sadly complete.

limerick_list.author: John Young
limerick_list.text:
Do have some madeira, m'dear,
And don't be afraid to come near.
I see that you're yawning—
Perhaps by the morning
My beard could be tickling your ear.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
I had doubts when I went for a sail.
Breezy weather turned into a gale.
The waters got aestuous:
Roiling, tempestuous.
Soon I hung over the rail.

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
Microtubules resembling a ray
Can form asters, biologists say.
When mitosis occurs,
There are systems of spurs
On the spindles like stars on display.

limerick_list.author: bob killian
limerick_list.text:
Masculinity comes with a set
Of rules real men can never forget.
Suppose that your weenie
Is shockingly teeny:
You must run out and buy a Corvette.

limerick_list.author: Jeff Foster
limerick_list.text:
The didgeridoo choir blew it:
That chord had such dissonance to it!
Asked alto to bass
(With a rather red face),
"Was my G flat, or did yer E do it?"

limerick_list.author: JimInRoses
limerick_list.text:
Though a deep-discount bond pays a pittance
(Not enough for a black sheep's remittance),
For the cents that you pay
You'll get dollars, some day,
If the issuer's there to make quittance.

limerick_list.author: Mad Kane
limerick_list.text:
They said my accounting was splendid,
But told me my contract had ended.
So why was I sacked?
My report showed they lacked
Enough cash—they were overextended.

limerick_list.author: timon
limerick_list.text:
On the wing of the skull's sphenoid bone
(Just in front of your ear — and your phone),
Should you batter Gaddafi on
This, the crotaphion,
He'd fall to the ground with a groan.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
"Guess who just got a haircut?"  "I see.
It's a flattop, and short as can be.
On a guy, I maintain,
Hair that's flat, like a plane,
Is OK; but on Jane?  Disagree!"

limerick_list.author: Val
limerick_list.text:
I'm alone in my home all this week
And, upstairs in my bed, hear a squeak;
I'm alert to each sound
Of the floorboards—and round
About midnight I freak at a creak.

limerick_list.author: John Young
limerick_list.text:
Encopresis: you hadn't a clue
That you needed to go to the loo.
Now you stand in distress;
There's a smell, and a mess,
As your pants are inflated by poo.

limerick_list.author: S. A. McBurnie
limerick_list.text:
A detractor's base sneer you'd erase,
And you long to make clear his disgrace?
If your tongue won't express
Your disdain and distress,
Turn your back with a sharp about-face.

limerick_list.author: Charles Silliman
limerick_list.text:
The crapshooter cried, "I can't lose,
Come on, babe needs a new pair of shoes!"
But his luck and shrill talkin'
Left baby still walkin'
Around with bare feet and the blues.

limerick_list.author: psheil
limerick_list.text:
Lexicographers, listen to me:
Coconspirator never should be
A graphical printer.
That meaning's a splinter,
A thought with which none should agree.

limerick_list.author: mrsrev
limerick_list.text:
Do you know what this beekeeper does
That has all of his bee club abuzz?
He works very hard
In his flowered back yard
Gathering honey. And why? Just because.

limerick_list.author: Tim Alborn
limerick_list.text:
If Mancunians, locked in a battle
In Glasgow, proceeded to prattle
'Bout Rangers, a stranger
Could use an arranger
For bidialectalist tattle.

limerick_list.author: PGS
limerick_list.text:
A fluid's a substance that moves,
In response to small forces. This proves
To be true for some masses,
Like liquids or gases,
And the mud underneath horses' hooves.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
A bugbear's not only for tots.
As a grown-up, I also have lots:
Telemarketers' calls,
Bosses busting my balls,
Drunken drivers, inflation, the trots.

limerick_list.author: Carol June Hooker
limerick_list.text:
Lose the unneeded "e" from "espy."
Ease yourself by forgiving the guy.
Though aphesis is slow
(Greek for "let the dreck go"),
On the whole, it is worthwhile to try.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
"Seven Teenagers Dead Due to Cheese!"
There's no humor in headlines like these.
Cheese is heroin cut
With cold remedies, but
The result can drop kids to their knees.

limerick_list.author: rusty
limerick_list.text:
Fall asleep at the wheel when you're making
A trip? That's a big risk you're taking.
Install AEB
And doze off worry-free
With our Auto Emergency Braking.

limerick_list.author: JimInRoses
limerick_list.text:
If your diet is like Gayelord Hauser's,
Get molasses delivered in bowsers
(Road tankers). With wheat
Germ and yogurt to eat,
You will soon feel the slack in your trousers.

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
On the Isle of Man, are there males?
And does China have tableware sales?
Is there turkey to eat
On an Ottoman seat?
Are cetologists living in Wales?

limerick_list.author: SusanL
limerick_list.text:
To go fishin' I dig me some crawlers
Cuz minnows, they cost a few dollars.
I ain't got me a dime,
But there's mountains of time
To hunt catfish down there in the hollers.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
I knitted a red crew neck sweater
For my pet—she's a young Irish setter.
Just one look at those threads
And she tore them to shreds—
Now she goes around nude, and I let 'er.

limerick_list.author: Robert Holland
limerick_list.text:
He told me, "Butt out of my life,
'Cause I'm up to my eyeballs in strife.
I can't take any more!
Get your ass out the door!
You are acting too much like my wife."

limerick_list.author: Howard Spindel
limerick_list.text:
Broke my arm on a Hollywood set —
Will they treat me? I'm deeply in debt.
But the doc said, "For you,
Someone nubile and new,
On my casting couch, plastered you'll get."

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
"I'm convinced that your alibi's fiction.
You've been caught in the wrong jurisdiction.
Contradictory facts
Show your criminal acts.
Twenty years!" cried the judge, with conviction.

limerick_list.author: David Franks
limerick_list.text:
"I tell you, you're indigent scum!"
The supplicant asked him, "How come?"
"You ask for, all whiny,
My on-the-fritz heinie:
You bum a bum bum, you're a bum!"

limerick_list.author: Goldie
StephenGold
limerick_list.text:
If invited to dine by a friend,
Do take wine, but (O Heaven forfend!)
Never buy cheap Shiraz,
Which your nose tells you has
Been exhumed from a musty bin-end.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
He's a silly Canadian, Bruce,
Who his friends all agree's a real goose.
Working hard to raise dough
For sane causes? Hell, no!
He's campaigning to ban moose abuse.

limerick_list.author: psh
limerick_list.text:
A sound golf tee holds balls off the ground.
The perceptive old links-man has found,
Whether made from fine wood
Or of plastic, folks should
Praise the pegs for long drives on a round.

limerick_list.author: Workshop
limerick_list.text:
These bureaus reporting my score
Make shopping so hard but not more
Than those trying to sue,
So credit is due
For the number of suits in my drawer.

limerick_list.author: D Frayer
limerick_list.text:
To the Christians, his work was abusive.
The True Discourse of Celsus: deducive
Polemic that called them
All fools and appalled them.
They found Origen's answer conclusive.

limerick_list.author: a.groovymind
limerick_list.text:
The sneering young skinhead in court
Was the type I would like to deport.
With tattooed Union Jack,
And that jaw hanging slack —
He was nasty and British, in short.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Disthronize is really a word
For dethrone, though it seems so absurd.
I cannot quite say whether
It's the most altogether
Ridiculous word I have heard.

limerick_list.author: Chris Young
limerick_list.text:
My routine is described as boylesque —
Not like SuBo in drag (how grotesque!).
No, my body's quite fit
And I show quite a bit
To the music that's cued at the desk.

limerick_list.author: Mary
limerick_list.text:
This chili sauce—yep, it's no fable:
Enchiladas or meat loaf—you're able,
With tomatoes' potential
(Chopped peppers—essential),
To add zest, fire, and zing to your table.

limerick_list.author: mike scholtes
limerick_list.text:
It's the course of all efforts that wend
From a start all the way to an end;
My anabasis fell
On its journey to hell
With an e-mail "To ALL", and a SEND.

limerick_list.author: Eredicus
limerick_list.text:
There once was a man from a shoe,
Who dreamt he was eating Peru—
Hey, wait! That's not right!
It's been altered, despite
My best efforts to keep this one true!

limerick_list.author: Qermaq and Jane Auerbach
limerick_list.text:
Stack all of the cars in the nation
On high at a single location.
When we measure, oblique,
From horizon to peak,
That's an angle of huge elevation!

limerick_list.author: kandabongo
limerick_list.text:
"You go KILL IT!  That vicious acaridan!"
Shrieked my wife, the malicious old harridan.
But the mite in her sight
Was not quite worth a fright—
Wish I'd married delicious Ann Sheridan.

limerick_list.author: Brian Cairns
limerick_list.text:
Dilemmas uniquely Aleutian,
Where a map must provide the solution:
Just how do you say
If tomorrow's today
Or if you're a Yank or a Roo-sian?

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
My grandfather Jake struck it rich.
Now he only wears clothing for which
He is carefully fitted,
And none is permitted
That hasn't a buttonhole stitch.

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
This crystalline ketone reduces
To acridine, known for its uses
In drugs and in dyes.
Since it's toxic, it's wise
To leave acridone out of your mousses.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
You look cylindroid, man; I can't see
Any bumps in your leg—just the knee,
And you once were so buff!
Are you eating enough?
Food and exercise, pal, that's the key.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
A French fork's a full beard with a split
At the chin. Pretty sharp, I'd submit.
Said a Johnny Depp fan,
"It looks good on a man,
But on women it's wholly unfit.

limerick_list.author: Richard English
limerick_list.text:
Abcoulomb: an electrical charge
(Ten coulombs and therefore not large)
Which, in copper voltameters,
Moves tiny diameters
Of copper (you won't need a barge).

limerick_list.author: Brian Cairns
limerick_list.text:
"Higher score wins the lot," said my friend—
And he threw three-and-two.  Don't depend
On my fortune, my son!
I threw ambs-ace (one-one).
My ill luck stayed intact till the end.

limerick_list.author: Basingstoke
limerick_list.text:
Callipygous: this word comes to mind
When regarding a well-honed behind.
There's no need to be crass
When you're making your pass:
With this term you will sound more refined.

limerick_list.author: Graham Lester
limerick_list.text:
Lord, we finally got into Canaan,
But we think you should do some explanaan.
Forty years isn't funny:
Where's the milk?  Where's the honey?
Where's the benefits promised in tranaan?

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
My wife's pregnant.  We work for Big Blue.
When our twins are born, here's what we'll do:
Name them "I.B." and "Em."
Folks will sure notice them!
They'll be company kids through and through.

limerick_list.author: lopey
limerick_list.text:
The mines labeled antipersonnel
A great many soldiers can fell,
So watch where you step.
Protect, please, our rep,
Plus our heads and our bodies as well.

limerick_list.author: VERaLOE
limerick_list.text:
The vacationland ('Pine Tree State"), Maine,
Has a namesake in France, not in Spain.
It's on Canada's border,
First in east-to-west order,
And York (Maine) was well loved by Mark Twain.

limerick_list.author: Tim Alborn
limerick_list.text:
The harlot was quick to applaud
After sex with her trick; she was awed
By his prowess. Poor chap—
He contracted the clap!
For his condom, quite clearly, was flawed.

limerick_list.author: BobHale
limerick_list.text:
In England they call it blue cheese
And devour just as much as they please.
From my book I can see
That in "Aust. and NZ"
It's blue vein that's the phrase that agrees.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
A drug dealer lives on my block,
Selling dangerous dope round the clock.
To the cops in our town,
I say: "Close the guy down!
It's unlikely he'll run out of stock."

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
One-eyed Moses, an old Ethiopian,
Thought his life and the world were Utopian,
Yet he'd howl when he would
Not be well understood
When he spoke of himself as cyclopean.

limerick_list.author: Jonathan Caws-Elwitt
limerick_list.text:
Does paperwork leave you agape?
This a bureaucrat cannot escape.
And I've even a hunch
That he bundles his lunch
In a package that's sealed with red tape.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
Embracing long peregrinations,
I embarked on sustained evagations.
I roved; such digression
Abated depression
And nurtured profound cerebrations.

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
The student they loved to harass
Had the boniest assets, alas.
But with surgery (plastic),
She turned out fantastic:
The bonniest lass in the class.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
I think deadcatting's what we should do,
As trouble is starting to brew.
We'll  leak a fake story
That's sexy or gory
To take the attention off you.

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
Tonight on TV, brother Arn'll
Be expecting to see something carnal.
When the movie, instead,
Shows the bodies all dead,
Then methinks he'll be changing the charnel.

limerick_list.author: D Frayer
limerick_list.text:
My attempt to determine her Asianness:
"Is that Chinese-ness, Miss, or Malaysian-ness?"
But she said, "I'm a Turk,
You big fat-headed jerk!"
My mistake's due to narrow Caucasian-ness.

limerick_list.author: timon
limerick_list.text:
My axe is conveniently fitted
With blades on both sides (double-bitted).
"Does that mean," asked some dunce,
"You cut both ways at once?"
(A question obtuse and half-witted).

limerick_list.author: Ritepath
limerick_list.text:
I see that his face has a frown;
Then perhaps with a word I will clown,
"May I help you devex?"
"Wrong word," he objects:
"That means 'sloping',  perhaps 'bending down'."

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
A dog owner might want to hold
A traditional party, I'm told:
A bark mitzvah for Ruff,
Serving liver and stuff,
Shouting, "Muzzle Tov! Thirteen years old!"

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
If the plural of hoof is spelled hooves,
Then it follows: one goof and two gooves.
"All English," say fools,
"Follows hard and fast rules,"
A theory this pairing disproves.

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
I've
been
programming
spreadsheets
for
weeks,
With
default
data
entry
techniques.
Since
their
scheme,
in
the
norm,
Is
columnar
in
form,
I
have
lim'ricks
requiring
some
tweaks.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Duodenum: the part of your gut
Where your stomach unloads itself, but
That acid expulser
Can cause a deep ulcer,
Requiring a surgeon to cut.

limerick_list.author: Jacqui Brown
limerick_list.text:
On a picnic I took a young redhead
And arranged outdoor fare on a bedspread.
There, under a willow,
She sought out a pillow
And fell fast asleep in the bread spread.

limerick_list.author: PGS
limerick_list.text:
A denominate number, as such,
Will tell you exactly how much
Of a property's found
In a weight of 3 pound:
And the unit's to serve as a crutch.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Our dim leader inspires no awe.
He is aweless, as everyone saw
When he shouted, "Fake news!"
At his first bad reviews.
From the spotlight I wish he'd withdraw.

limerick_list.author: Celia Warren
limerick_list.text:
All our streets, they are chocka today.
Can I cross the road safely? No way!
Cars sit bumper to bumper.
I need a pole jumper
To help me avoid more delay.

limerick_list.author: rusty
limerick_list.text:
Done the trick was once quite untoward,
As its meanings were not in accord:
There was (1) "(Up) You've won!",
And too (2) "(Down) You're done!".
Cleft like cleave, 'twas a double-edged sword.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Says a man from Darjeeling named Matt,
"Our famed Ealing-bound tram's where it's at!
We declare with great pride
You'll enjoy a fine ride
(Just as long as you're wearing a hat)."

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
Planned a party as big as they get;
Went in hock for a band and Joan Jett.
Sent out invites — a ton.
The replies? Not a one!
Now I'm dreading a fête worse than debt.

limerick_list.author: Carol O
limerick_list.text:
Were you born in the fifties? That time
Saw the birth rate dramatically climb;
So you know it's no rumor—
You're one baby boomer
Of millions approaching their prime.

limerick_list.author: Paperdragon
limerick_list.text:
Logging in at the office, I'm shocked.
The security settings are locked.
I can no longer shirk
When I'm here at my work
As my access to this site is blocked.

limerick_list.author: Janet McConnaughey
limerick_list.text:
"I know dinghy!" I shout, as a boast:
"Rowed on rivers, or sailed on the coast,
It's an Indian boat;
The word's Hindi." I gloat.
No one else knows it all. I'm the most.

limerick_list.author: Richard Stehr
limerick_list.text:
Star of Ibsen's most time-honored play
Slew a turkey for Thanksgiving Day.
Said the actress, "I never
Imagined I ever
Would behead a gobbler this way."

limerick_list.author: Goldie
limerick_list.text:
My memory so often stalls
When I'm sizing and loading my balls.
Let's see  — small ones are duck shot
And big ones are buckshot,
But others are really tough calls.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
Folks feel heavy from bagels. Instead,
We'll go crunchy and small with our bread,
Adding fruit trays and wine—
It all falls into line.
Buy some bagel chips; I'll make a spread.

limerick_list.author: David
limerick_list.text:
Had you spotted my clues, my rhymes jolly would
Have shown you which Film Mecca's folly would
Be featured here. Golly,
Not Hollywood, Molly —
The much bigger film centre, Bollywood!

limerick_list.author: JimInRoses
limerick_list.text:
You are still pumping iron, so you say,
And you run seven miles every day.
But you say "supersize"
Buying milkshakes or fries:
Your chubbedness gives you away.

limerick_list.author: Roger Vick
limerick_list.text:
For inflicting extreme wear and tear,
Carborundum is hard to compare.
If there's something to grind
It's right there—but to find
It in nature's remarkably rare.

limerick_list.author: Carl Lands
Andrew Burnet
limerick_list.text:
Darlin' Clementine, orange of skin,
Sweet and ripe was she. Hell, it's a sin!
She done drowned in the river,
May the Good Lord furgiv'er.
My tree's never bore fruit agin.

limerick_list.author: alkahuna
limerick_list.text:
The Bulgarian priest Bogomil
Had a dualist truth to reveal.
He said Jesus's brother
Was Satan, no other!
(This schism took decades to heal.)

limerick_list.author: sallycello
limerick_list.text:
A buck passer's one who excuses
His errors with rank he misuses.
If the buck's passed to you
There is grief to ensue,
Since you'll be the guy he abuses.

limerick_list.author: hugh t.
limerick_list.text:
A zebra, imported to Italy
For the Vatican Zoo, observed wittily:
"Though myself I am bichrome,
For its colour I like Rome,
And I think I contrast very prettily."

limerick_list.author: Jason Talbott
limerick_list.text:
The captain blew up when he learned
Of the brawl between sailors, which earned
A consectary trip
To the side of the ship
Where he keelhauled all parties concerned.

limerick_list.author: Roger Dunn
limerick_list.text:
I thought Fold, then the dealer said, "Hey!
Up the ante? Well, whadya say?"
Like a moth round a flame
I felt trapped in their game,
But for those kinds of odds? "Yes, I'll play."

limerick_list.author: Chuck Folkers
limerick_list.text:
At the bean feast, the boss was a hoot:
He came dressed in a rubberized suit
And regaled the whole staff,
Making everyone laugh
With his ode to the musical fruit.

limerick_list.author: Goldie
limerick_list.text:
Baba Yaga, Tom Thumb, Pecos Bill,
Davy Crockett, Rapunzel, Joe Hill,
Casey Jones, et al., act
To mix folklore with fact —
Here are stories that time can not kill.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
The prefix c o- means "as one"
Or "together" or "help with work done"
Like co-pilots.  You're sunk
Should they both show up drunk.
Your adventure has only begun.

limerick_list.author: mike scholtes
limerick_list.text:
While Blake saw the world in a flower,
In knowledge, today, we see power.
With minimal fuss,
Both arrive on a bus,
But the drivers can tend to be sour.

limerick_list.author: Carol June Hooker
limerick_list.text:
What rare colors did army types grab
From the muddy gray shades at their lab?
Not pastels, nothing light,
Nothing vivid or bright—
They were khaki- or olive-dyed drab.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
"At the protest, we'll strip, me and you.
We'll get coverage out the wazoo!"
Though I'm down with her views
("Down with taxes on booze!"),
All that month I was down with the flu.

limerick_list.author: Jim Vincent
Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Rhyme and meter are key,
When combined with divine inspiration,
For your limerick to be a creation
That's as sharp as can be,
But what kills it? Disorganization!

limerick_list.author: Giorgio Coniglio
limerick_list.text:
All Saints' Eve yields a jest that's suggestive:
Cemeterians' charges grow restive.
Can we face with aplomb
A mass uprising zom-
bie, infesting our trick-or-treat festive?

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
A long battery of tests lies before us
With committees of scholars to score us.
We hope, once we're through
With this grueling review,
That the Ivies won't choose to ignore us.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
Though she takes neither coffee nor tea,
Kathy's caffeinated, perky and free.
Would you tame her? Beware.
She's got spirit to spare.
Lock her up, man… then give me the key.

limerick_list.author: John Weigel
limerick_list.text:
You're awake in your bed with a dread:
Has the trust in your partner so fled
That you dream of his flight
With your money each night,
To absquatulate off to Club Med?

limerick_list.author: BobHale
limerick_list.text:
"Does sir dress to the left or the right?"
Asked the tailor, just being polite.
With equipment so small,
Did it matter at all
If the crotch was a little too tight?

limerick_list.author: Roger Vick
limerick_list.text:
Unaware of the capsid nymphs there
On my pear trees in spring, I'd no care.
But my harvest is thwarted:
Fruit's lumpy, contorted.
Those sap-suckers won. I despair.

limerick_list.author: Aliza
limerick_list.text:
I once took a trip to Calcutta,
Where folks cook with ghee 'stead of butter.
They speak in Bengali;
It's all rather jolly,
Except for the poor in the gutter.

limerick_list.author: Dottie
limerick_list.text:
Just as well diagnostical tests can
Detect little lumps that our chests can
Brew up. But we'd wish
Our boobs less of a squish
When we go for our annual breast scan.

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
10 p.m. on the fourth of July,
Pyrotechnics begin in the sky.
Though displays of red, white,
Blue, and green are a sight,
These loud fireworks make pets and tots cry.

limerick_list.author: Graham Lester
MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
Cataclysmists are prophets of doom.
There's a dumb one in front of the room,
Talking super-volcano
And how it'll rain o-
ver us tons of dust, with a BOO—

limerick_list.author: proof
limerick_list.text:
I determined to master Swahili
And speak like a native. Yes, really.
It was my choice, of course,
Without pressure or force.
I enrolled in the language class freely.

limerick_list.author: zqms
Tim Alborn
limerick_list.text:
A flamingo, a dove, and a hawk,
An albatross, penguin, and auk:
They're all avifauna,
Cohabiting on a
Few chunks of Galapagos rock.

limerick_list.author: Val
limerick_list.text:
The eye is the organ of sight,
Though, in man, it can't penetrate night.
You need both of your eyes
To gauge distance and size
So the world, in 3D, is viewed right.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
That's a Challenger, Jack's brand new toy,
Because Jack's a great big little boy.
"Man, this Dodge really kicks,"
He says, "Look, a V-6!"
With his cars, Jack is not a dull boy.

limerick_list.author: Ruchiccio
limerick_list.text:
From the shelf in the cupboard I'll free ya.
I'll light ya where all of us see ya.
With candles in line
You're aflame, you're divine.
Now it's your turn to shine, chanukiah!

limerick_list.author: Carol June Hooker
limerick_list.text:
When Philip and Margaret bought land
Near Margaret's parents in Scotland,
Its tight cozy cottage
Smelt largely of pottage;
Its front, back, and side yards were cotland.

limerick_list.author: Roger Dunn
limerick_list.text:
Someone kidnapped or squad-snatched could be
Held for ransom  — a deal to set free.
Being forcibly met,
Dragged away under threat
Earns the victim the name abductee.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Some limericks rhyme moon, June, and spoon
Til I want to escape to Cancún,
Where the women are plenty
And muy caliente,
Each crooning a Mexican tune.

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
The Patriots, 18 and 0,
Were the favorites to win the big show.
With determined defiance,
The underdog Giants
Surprisingly conquered their foe.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
In our church, there's Kim Basinger, lay singer.
Never weak, she's a loud all-the-way singer.
In a cab, as a passenger:
"Hey, look! It's Kim Basinger!"
"Glad to meetcha, but please, it's Kim Basinger."

limerick_list.author: Goldie
limerick_list.text:
You poor mousie, I knew you were doomed,
In a sinewy coil entombed.
I convey consolation
For your devoration:
My python your carcass consumed.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
"Saw this word in an ad on the telly;
Does it rhyme," queried Shelly, "with belly?"
"It means 'grade school and high school'—
Younger brother's and my school."
"What? 'el-HIE'? But its spelling's like Delhi!"

limerick_list.author: JimInRoses
limerick_list.text:
Descriptivism says that my morals
(Value judgements) should never cause quarrels.
My deep motivation
Defies demonstration;
I rest on inscrutable laurels.

limerick_list.author: Roger Vick
limerick_list.text:
Capybaras are rodents, serene,
And the largest that we've ever seen.
Land or water's their home,
And in groups they will roam.
Grass and reeds are their daily cuisine.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
My hubby drinks beer until near-full,
Making passes, and acting drunk-cheerful.
I throw beer that's ice cold
At an ear when I scold,
To give  the bum double an earful.

limerick_list.author: proof
limerick_list.text:
Look, your risk with a jury is great.
They don't like that you murdered your mate.
But your miserly judge
Doesn't bear you a grudge.
Let that domesman (plus cash) set your fate.

limerick_list.author: Chris Young
limerick_list.text:
¡Madre mia! I have un problema.
I phone my querida, sweet Gemma,
And promise her sex.
But who answers? My ex!
What to do, now I see I dial Emma?

limerick_list.author: Kevin
limerick_list.text:
The Irish-born statesman Ed Burke
Was much more than an average clerk.
The remarks on his banners
("Less laws and more manners")
Drove many opponents berserk.

limerick_list.author: Celia Warren
limerick_list.text:
Bottle green, like those ten on the wall,
Neither yellow nor blue — see them fall.
When one drops out of line,
That will only leave nine
Deep green bottles of glass ... is that all?

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
East by north, to a child, may appear
Just the same as due east, but don't jeer.
If they'd ask, I'd submit
It's more north—just a bit.
That's why kids can't be pirates, it's clear.

limerick_list.author: CruzerX
limerick_list.text:
You're spreading this trash (I've the feeling).
Your calumny's leaving me reeling.
How dare you besmirch
Such a fine name as Birch?
I borrowed those cars; that's not stealing.

limerick_list.author: Jeter Coffee
limerick_list.text:
The OEDILF is a fabulous site —
I've lingered at times half the night.
And should sleeplessness weigh
Down my eyelids next day,
I'll go back for more lim'rick delight.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
When mass murder at Anytown flares,
A condolent, sad, phrase says one cares.
From sad mouths one can hear
Hackneyed words insincere:
"Thoughts and prayers!" "Thoughts and prayers!" "Thoughts and prayers!"

limerick_list.author: speedysnail
limerick_list.text:
In Christchurch, the South Island city,
The churches looked ever so pretty,
Until a big quake
Gave 'em all a good shake
And a bunch tumbled down. Such a pity.

limerick_list.author: Carol O
limerick_list.text:
An awning of canvas gives shade
Over windows and doorways of trade.
This strong cotton canopy
Shelters a panoply
Of wares being proudly displayed.

limerick_list.author: Jeff Foster
limerick_list.text:
The man in seat 32B
Encroachingly shifted his knee—
An act which exhibited
Scorn for prohibited
Airspace of 32C!

limerick_list.author: Shelby Forrest
limerick_list.text:
Jane was pinched from behind on a train.
By whom, she could not ascertain.
The culprit they sought,
But he never was caught.
He's a master at legerdemain.

limerick_list.author: Celia Warren
limerick_list.text:
These two banking pins dampen the rock
Of the levers inside this old clock.
My full knowledge about them:
Oscillation without them
Could mess up the tick and the tock.

limerick_list.author: Frank Hubeny
limerick_list.text:
Aetiology wants to know why
All that is is the way it is. I
Do not actually care,
But suspect that somewhere
There's a cause I could blame if I try.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
A man with a bark may remark
That from bark he had fashioned his ark.
He'll embark (and not park)
Without sound, in the dark
If his poodles agree not to bark.

limerick_list.author: Roger Dunn
limerick_list.text:
It's said, "silence is golden," that's why
I don't suffer disquiet when I,
By exploiting its use,
Fend off someone's abuse
With my silent but gilding reply.

limerick_list.author: Derek Redfern and asjchae
limerick_list.text:
Eat grilled seafood, not beef, to be thinner;
For good health, have fresh salmon: a winner.
In the rivers they teem
As they swim up the stream
Where some fisheries catch them for dinner.

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
I'm blessed with deep pockets.  I mean
That I'm affluent, rolling in green.
Lots of wealth I amass.
Like the movies' top brass
Filming smut, what I make is obscene.

limerick_list.author: Celia Warren
limerick_list.text:
From a walk to a bit of a trot —
Now a canter — so fast, I'm red hot!
Riding Pegasus, soon
I'll be reaching the moon
At a gallop. I like speed a lot!

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
A didrachma's a two-drachma piece
Made of silver. Used where? Ancient Greece.
Could a Sparta-based carter,
Unwilling to barter,
At a drachma apiece, buy two geese?

limerick_list.author: Reia Light
limerick_list.text:
Since the battery died in my truck,
By the side of the highway I'm stuck.
I've got no signal flares,
So cars pass, unawares—
With no lights, I'm quite hidden. Well...

limerick_list.author: skipjordan
limerick_list.text:
An extructor (a builder) named Heep:
"I build coops for small fowls that peep.
I don't charge you big bucks,
And my work's not deluxe,
But I'll do a nice job on the cheap."

limerick_list.author: Workshop
limerick_list.text:
I got back at my nasty old teacher:
"You attempt to appear like a preacher,
But your sermons sound false,
Like four beats in a waltz.
You are such an unsavoury creature!"

limerick_list.author: mike scholtes
limerick_list.text:
Our clean, simple cosmos got dirty:
An object like BL Lacertae
That looks like a quasar
Is known as a blazar
If synchrotron beaming is spurty.

limerick_list.author: Matt Schweizer
limerick_list.text:
My accordian band will not play
In American dance halls today.
So we're heading to France,
Where they'll give us a chance,
Bal musette: where the music is gay!

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
"So tomorrow we knock off the creep,
And I promise that no one will weep.
With a big day ahead
You should all go to bed.
Can the chat. Douse the lights. Go to sleep."

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
If I keep up the hunt for this game bird
(In the wild—the Crypturi's no tame bird),
And I aim with my rifle,
But jerk it a trifle,
I'll catch me a living-but-lame bird.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
He's an admiral, they say, of the seas
That are narrow. It's sure to displease
If this foul, drunken chap
Should throw up in your lap
From your gut all the way to your knees.

limerick_list.author: Kevin Dopart
limerick_list.text:
A cook in the Army named Pearl,
Gave the guys in the mess quite a twirl.
Although draining to give,
'Twas her duty to sieve —
They loved dating this colander girl.

limerick_list.author: Bluebelle
limerick_list.text:
I stand rooted, my feet on the ground,
With my hands on my tummy's slight mound,
And feel energy rise
That, with chi from the skies,
Helps my centre of balance stay round.

limerick_list.author: Dave Jermy
limerick_list.text:
Near the Broad Street pump, folk started dying
When cholera hit them. Defying
His peers, Doctor Snow
Had them stop the pump's flow,
Showing water at fault, no denying.

limerick_list.author: Carol June Hooker
limerick_list.text:
It's Black History Month.  Reverend King,
While we lift ev'ry voice and sing, cling
To your dream of equality.
Demonstrate polity,
Tubman; Obama, take wing!

limerick_list.author: GalFisk
limerick_list.text:
Granularity (also called graininess)
Means how granular stuff is. (What braininess!)
For a solid that splits
Into lots of small bits,
It's descriptive. (For liquids, it's raininess.)

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
It's finocchio—give some a try!
As a spice, it's a very good buy.
It's like anise, not bland,
Found in sausages, and
It will make your nose grow if you lie.

limerick_list.author: Michael Toalster
limerick_list.text:
If others determined before
That five strokes are a "par" target score
For this golf hole, your three
Are an eagle. But, gee,
My "ostrich" means seventeen more.

limerick_list.author: alan meyer
limerick_list.text:
Hail "Gustavo the Great" Dudamel —
Gifted maestro now doing quite well.
From L.A. to Milan,
Georges Bizet to Don Juan,
Just how high will he fly?  Who can tell?

limerick_list.author: JimInRoses
limerick_list.text:
London's Aldersgate, Moorgate and Bish-
opsgate, Ludgate and Newgate will dish
All outsiders who planned
To invade us by land.
If by water, there's Billingsgate (fish).

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
When I planned my vacation to ski,
My thermometer read 23,
But the slope where I go
Wasn't covered by snow,
Since the temperature scale was in C.

limerick_list.author: Carol O
limerick_list.text:
The succulent green aloe vera:
A plant whose soft gel can repair ya.
On your skin put a dab
For a burn, scrape, or scab;
It's the purest first aid of our era.

limerick_list.author: Scott Campisi
limerick_list.text:
For the plant buffs, a quick education:
Acrocarpous suggests germination
Where the fruit would extend
From the stalk at its end,
Which is terminal fructification.

limerick_list.author: Jesse Frankovich
limerick_list.text:
Corporations are run by a board
Of directors and owned by a horde
Of investors who'd like
The firm's profits to spike,
Since they'll share in its every reward.

limerick_list.author: Steve Ngai
limerick_list.text:
A chap who was musically bored
Changed the fifth of his dominant chord:
By a half step he raised it
("Augmented," he phrased it)—
His V-to-I movement's adored.

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
In a port near Marseilles, a coquette
Playing tennis approaches the net:
"I do not know the score
Since your point and, what's more,
What's this town called?" "It's game, match, and Cette!"

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
The fuzz paid some clams for a chat
With some guy in the hood who's a rat.
As they fished for some tips,
He was loose with his lips:
With a squeal, he had fingered some cat.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
The surgeon I'd thought was a friend
Put in sutures, my backside to mend.
Deadened nerves left me numbed.
I can't walk, so I'm bummed;
Our relationship reached a dead end.

limerick_list.author: Jeff Foster
limerick_list.text:
The butterfly said to the bee
(Combatively), "Why don't we see,
In a head-to-head fight,
If your sting or my flight
Gave the edge to Muhammad Ali?"

limerick_list.author: speedysnail
limerick_list.text:
The chapati, a flat wholemeal bread,
Is a food on which Hindus are fed.
Don't spread it with jam
Or with Vegemite, ma'am:
It's intended for curries instead.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Another clean air act? I seethe,
And my poisonous pen I unsheathe
To defend all my clients—
Industrial giants.
(Who cares whether people can breathe?)

limerick_list.author: Meg Beagle
limerick_list.text:
Anuran?  It's only a frog,
With long legs and no tail, in its bog.
If you kiss it, you'll wince;
It won't change to a prince.
It'll just hop away in the fog.

limerick_list.author: Mad Kane
limerick_list.text:
Some bigots who visited Cannes
Demanded a gay-movie ban
And, in ads quite extensive,
They screamed, "It's offensive!"
They failed; viewers raved to a man.

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
A big fish in a very small pond
Hoped success would develop beyond
Just his village.  A pity,
The folks in the city—
That market—just didn't respond.

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
Albacete's a region in Spain
Where the vintners keep track of the rain.
There are different stats
For the mountains and flats.
Does the rain mainly stay in the plain?

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
"You're a fool," Lady Underleigh said,
"To disport in your fieldworker's bed.
He's a son of the soil;
You'll soon own Father's oil,
And he know's it. Try polo instead."

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Oh, those dactylists, boy, they're humdingers!
How the mem'ry of dactylists lingers!
Whether epic or terse,
They write "DAH-da-da" verse.
(Did you think that they ate with their fingers?)

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
The blasphemousness, friend, of your curse?
It's inviting some lightning, or worse.
First you "God-damned" His name,
Then said He is to blame
For the hell in men's lives. How perverse!

limerick_list.author: Richard English
limerick_list.text:
If in Georgia you happen to see
A plant with large leaves hanging free
And with bark of bright green,
Well, you've probably seen
A young Chinese parasol tree.

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
General Mills has a gal of their making.
Betty Crocker took questions on baking.
Soon their marketing game
Put a face to the name,
But just how many knew they were faking?

limerick_list.author: Recumbentman
limerick_list.text:
Butter up any person who lets you.
Heap praise on whoever abets you.
If candour offends,
It won't further your ends,
So use flattery—see where it gets you.

limerick_list.author: Jim Vincent
limerick_list.text:
Come see Bip as he dons his chapeau,
Set to pantomime, face all aglow.
Scenes unseen he creates
As he moonwalks and skates.
What a character! (Vintage Marceau.)

limerick_list.author: zqms
limerick_list.text:
If you're planning to go to the pix
For a bloodfest, do not invite chicks.
Watching bloodshed on screen,
They can get really mean
And pick up many handy new tricks.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
The aduncity certainly shows
At the core of his face where his nose
Is curved inward and bent
To a grievous extent.
It scares children wherever he goes.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Right after his recitativo,
Ron's singing was fast (presto vivo),
But showing such feeling
It set us all reeling—
Revealing, intense, espressivo.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Though a fanjet is large and it's noisy,
It will get you from Dallas to Boise
In a fast-moving plane.
But it wouldn't be sane,
From Noo Yawk, if you hopped one to Joisey.

limerick_list.author: Val
limerick_list.text:
Little hairs along eyelids abound
On the edges, and sometimes astound;
Extra eyelashes, mixed
With those growing, and fixed,
Both enhance and allure, girls have found.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
At that hell-hole the rescue took place.
Pain and joy were both etched on his face.
But that extricated man,
Extracted per plan,
Suffers flashbacks he cannot erase.

limerick_list.author: mike scholtes
limerick_list.text:
Giving clues at pronouncing is nice,
And they needn't be super-precise.
Even "AYN-shent ee-JIP-shehn",
In our broad transcription,
You'd speak without further advice.

limerick_list.author: C Wayne R
limerick_list.text:
In life, he accomplished his mission —
For this was his only ambition:
He'd avoided all stops
Where he'd hear from the cops,
"Get down in the kneeling position!"

limerick_list.author: Mad Kane
limerick_list.text:
This outage has led me to think
I've gone bonkers, berserk—need a shrink.
I keep checking the site.
It's still down—what a plight!
Web withdrawal may drive me to drink.

limerick_list.author: Roger Vick
limerick_list.text:
He'd been killed by a man-eating shark.
When I made a condolent remark
To his grief-stricken bride
She said thanks; she then cried
That its bite was much worse than its bark.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
Son, your wife's taking life on the chin,
So step up, help her do for her kin.
They'll need basics and care,
So be patient… be there.
And forbearance is where you begin.

limerick_list.author: dave newton
limerick_list.text:
An apogeotropic leaf's skill
Is to point itself up from the hill
In which the plant's planted.
Don't take it for granted—
Most leaves obey gravity's will.

limerick_list.author: Bob Dvorak
limerick_list.text:
A belt's not required to dance,
But you ought to leave nothing to chance.
With a few belts of Scotch,
A fine yuppie named Koch
Went to bed and woke up without pants.

limerick_list.author: Edmund Conti
limerick_list.text:
The limerick form is concise.
Its rules, quite precise, should suffice.
Remember, be terse
When composing the verse
And don't be a smut-case.  Be nice!

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
The sulfonimide sulfamethoxazole
(Not the other one—called sulfisoxazole)
With trimethoprim mixed
Has bacteria nixed
In the medicine called co-trimoxazole.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
"The invaders cannot carry on
With our signposts deranged or just gone."
"Wait — the signs moved or tossed?
This explains why I'm lost.
Is that Ipswich ahead or San Juan?"

limerick_list.author: Bob Dvorak
limerick_list.text:
"The Virgin's appeared!" the men cried;
They produced some "ex-cripples" who lied.
Chicanery breeds
The "Church in the Weeds"
And they'll fleece devotees far and wide.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
Said the centipede, "This is a bitch:
You ask which leg I move after which?"
The depth of this question
Caused neural congestion;
Stunned, immobile, he fell in a ditch.

limerick_list.author: StephenGold
limerick_list.text:
From the pulpit, his voice came a-roaring
Dire warnings, haranguing, imploring;
Trapped like rats in the pews,
We poor Boers would all muse,
"Jesus Christ, our new dominee's boring!"

limerick_list.author: Chris Young
limerick_list.text:
I brought furs for this trip with my neighbour:
To the British Antarctic, we'd labour.
But it's hot on this cruise —
Caribbean??? BQ's
Now Bonaire, Sint Eustatius and Saba?!!!

limerick_list.author: S. A. McBurnie and Snowy Owl
limerick_list.text:
My country and I are depressed,
For our values are shaky at best.
We have traded ideals
For more automobiles;
Now by anomie we are possessed.

limerick_list.author: speedysnail
limerick_list.text:
I was clueless. "What happened? Oh, poo!
I hit Enter, and now the screen's blue.
Does it mean that it's dead,
Or it doesn't like red?
To be honest, I haven't a clue."

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
Our son's lit'rally lousy; his head's
Full of galloping dandruff. The bed's
Clearly crawling as well.
It's the louse ranch from hell.
Commence nit-picking; I'll burn the spreads.

limerick_list.author: rusty
limerick_list.text:
Behind the bead curtain she lies,
Barely clad, batting dark bedroom eyes.
Through its strands snatch a glimpse
Of the curves that her pimp's
Vied to sell (and it keeps out the flies).

limerick_list.author: Jim Vincent
limerick_list.text:
"See that dove flitting downwards? The giver
Of life now descends to the river
To land on that man."
"Is this part of God's plan?"
"I don't know, but that voice makes me shiver."

limerick_list.author: Len Farano
limerick_list.text:
While asleep, Samuel heard the Lord's plea.
He woke Eli:  "What wish you of me?"
"You've been summoned, of course,
But you've got the wrong source.
Listen up, or get caller ID."

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
We're a bull gang repairing the road
Where the shoulder's begun to erode.
But we've ground to a halt
(Our ecologist's fault):
We've uncovered a rare rainbow toad.

limerick_list.author: art bates
limerick_list.text:
Sitting 'round in the campfire's light,
Jake oft' told of the violent fight
That he'd had with the snake,
And the boots he would make—
And the tale would grow taller each night.

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
It's a case or a cupboard with doors,
A collection of stamps or of spores.
It's a room holding art,
Or advisors so smart
They've agreed to our President's wars.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
The bay lynx is agile and muscular;
He hunts both the large and minuscular.
On a deer he may pounce,
Or a grasshopper's bounce
May attract in the dusk—he's crepuscular.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
A dipeptide's a chemical that
Can be hydrolyzed, right off the bat.
Amino acids you'll get.
Each dipeptide, I'll bet,
Yields two acids in one second flat.

limerick_list.author: Meg Beagle
limerick_list.text:
With funds at this time downright scanty,
I won't likely up this game's ante.
If I fail to win,
I might lose my skin
To a gambler turned armed vigilante.

limerick_list.author: Partypoet
limerick_list.text:
All the onlookers studied her feet
As her skirt swished in time to the beat.
They all would agree — a
Superb bulería!
Flamenco — a real Spanish treat!

limerick_list.author: Thomas Taylor
limerick_list.text:
You slouch, wretched Brit, round the fort
As if training and drill are as naught.
And you drink till you're plastered,
Britunculus bastard!
You'll jump when I file my report.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Look at b, d, f, h, k, l, t—
Seven lowercase letters, you see.
Each one's an ascender;
They seem taller, more slender
Than c, m, n, o, r, or v.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Every book in our school, every text,
Is degenderized; kids are perplexed.
When a sex text surrenders,
And stops naming genders,
We shrug and we wonder—what's next?

limerick_list.author: Amergin
limerick_list.text:
Forget feta, halloumi, ricotta!
Our own sheep milk cheese is much hotter.
If you visit our valley
In Poland's Podhale,
Try bundz, then mulled wine and sheep's trotter!

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
You needn't consult a presidium
Or purchase a ring with iridium
If you wish to explore
The conidiophore,
As it sexlessly makes the conidium.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Will the weeds in my yard be destroyed
By the chemical spray you've employed?
Are they really exterminable,
Or will some remain germinable—
And regrow? If that's so, I'm annoyed.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Might King Friday XIII renounce
His small crown? Heavens, no! Ounce for ounce
He does more for his realm
Backing art at the helm
Of a group even Fred can't pronounce.

limerick_list.author: Paperdragon
limerick_list.text:
Oh, poo, to the Matters of State!
Let these egg-stealing pigs meet their fate.
One must launch Angry Birds
At the green, grunting herds.
We are Queen, and the P.M. can wait.

limerick_list.author: BobHale
limerick_list.text:
As I caught in the forest today
An evocative smell, a bouquet,
I remembered when we
Carved our names on a tree:
A memory I'd hidden away.

limerick_list.author: bob killian
limerick_list.text:
In Slovakian jousts, goes the tale,
Will the chain mail or plating prevail?
Choose the bold Magyar lad,
Sturdy cast-iron-clad —
The Czech is (alas) in the mail.

limerick_list.author: Bob Dvorak
limerick_list.text:
A gopher, exceedingly thorough,
Finds a field's most felicitous furrow.
It's a suitable start;
Time to practice his art —
To claw through the earth and to burrow.

limerick_list.author: Len Farano
limerick_list.text:
Bilking widows: the felony charge
'Gainst midget, false psychic, Miss Marge.
But this seer got free.
The police APB:
Attention, small medium at large.

limerick_list.author: Chris Young
limerick_list.text:
My pin-up girl? That's Margaret Thatcher.
No latter-day Tory can match her.
Though my fancies aren't blue,
My right arm follows through
As my swift wrist-flicked missiles dispatch her.

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
This sausage is smoky and chewy,
Adds spice to a bland ratatouille.
But it's made out of pork,
So put down that fork.
It's not kosher to nosh on andouille.

limerick_list.author: Sussexdownsman
limerick_list.text:
If you're yearning to feel fine and dandy,
Then a dune buggy's really quite handy.
Yes, for fun on the sand,
That RV is just grand.
I once bought one for darling wife Sandie.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
There is padding inside of this tank,
So the air seems quite stale, to be frank.
But the crash pads will aid
If we're caught in a raid
And get bumped—the designers we'll thank.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Old Calchas, a seer and priest,
Told his king, "Sire the west wind has ceased,
So to cross the great water,
Give the goddess your daughter,
And to Troy you can voyage, at least."

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
The bride says she's feeling some stress
And is fighting the urge to obsess
Over some of the things
That her wedding day brings,
Which include a new name and a dress.

limerick_list.author: PGS
limerick_list.text:
"What's a blackbody?" asked my pal Jack.
"A small hole, with a hohlraum, looks black.
Light rays fall through this hole in
The cavity, strollin',
But hardly can find their way back."

limerick_list.author: Lanny
limerick_list.text:
At McNeil River Falls, the brown bear
Lets photographers click without care.
Ursus arctos by name,
He's indifferent, not tame,
If they'll only stay out of his hair.

limerick_list.author: rusty
limerick_list.text:
We're The (big happy criminal) Family!
We shamelessly, sham-ily, scam-ily
Defraud, forge, cheat, thieve,
Kidnap, rob and deceive,
And we do it all don't-give-a-damn-ily.

limerick_list.author: waterrocks
limerick_list.text:
"Nope, you're cold. Freezing cold. Cold as ice,"
She says gleefully. (Sisters... so nice.)
"Oh, that's warmer... a bit...
Nope, you're cold." Let me quit!
I've explored the whole house, almost — twice!

limerick_list.author: OldFitzer
limerick_list.text:
Devastation engenders much grief,
For of land, life and limb, it's a thief.
Often, anguish and pain
Will be all that remain,
Since from ruin there's no quick relief.

limerick_list.author: Jeff Foster
limerick_list.text:
Yvette, an inveterate auditor,
Overheard things, and nobody spauditor.
She'd even hear leaves drop —
Le Société Eavesdrop,
On hearing this, lavishly lauditor.

limerick_list.author: James Dobson
limerick_list.text:
Try psychology—study the mind;
Prefix criminal—sadly you'll find
That the brain of a felon
Is likely to dwell on
Those schemes that won't profit mankind.

limerick_list.author: psh
limerick_list.text:
Owl and Pussy-cat hastened the plot
When they daysailed in Pea-green, a yacht.
That ephemeral act,
Though it's fiction in fact,
Led this couple to tying the knot.

limerick_list.author: Celia Warren
limerick_list.text:
How the market can shrink and then grow!
This you might have heard called ebb and flow.
As the tides of the ocean
Show low and high motion,
So businesses, too, come and go.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
At inspection, the pigs were all fine,
And a clean bill of health given mine,
But actinobacillosis,
With a fatal prognosis,
Infected and killed off my swine.

limerick_list.author: Howard Spindel
limerick_list.text:
Slartibartfast received an award,
For in Norway his artistry soared.
With his coastline's design
Now refined to divine,
He's perfected his Model A Fjord.

limerick_list.author: Janet McConnaughey
limerick_list.text:
If something accordions, see,
Its pleats squeeze and stretch, hassle-free.
You can show it with type:
VVV|||VVV|||VVV.

limerick_list.author: mrsrev
limerick_list.text:
A Bemba said, "Let's sail the seas—
Away! Far from Zambia, please."
They set off by boat
On a very long float,
And wound up as Vietnamese!

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
The mambas of genus Dendraspis
Are snakes, though they're not Atractaspis.
Both are dangerous creatures
With poisonous features.
We're much better off with a raspis.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
When I heard "global warming," I felt
That the ice up in Greenland would melt.
Now I find every glacier
Is facing erasure—
By deglaciation grown svelte.

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
My ex wears the lovemaking crown.
He's a circus performer in town.
With no suitor out there
Who can even compare,
There's no filling the shoes of that clown.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
An arhat will never be frightened,
Though his senses are probably heightened.
This stage is the chief
Goal of Buddhist belief:
An arhat is one who's enlightened.

limerick_list.author: mike scholtes
limerick_list.text:
If a phone to ETs I design,
Just how many could pick up the line?
The equation by Drake
Tells the count: give or take
Several powers of ten, I'd say "nine"!

limerick_list.author: Bob Dvorak
limerick_list.text:
There once was a tennis man, Schwartz,
Who cared naught what was thought of his shorts.
So he looked 'bout as cute as
A guy in Bermudas
Could possibly look on the courts.

limerick_list.author: waterrocks
limerick_list.text:
• These points are remarkably clear.
• There's no dense clump of writing to fear.
• Let me start a new line.
• With a blob there, it's fine!
• Have you learnt about bullet points here?

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
I got called up to Major League Ball—
A cup of coffee with Philly was all.
Seven days in "The Show"
(It's my hummer—too slow),
So goodbye to my place in the Hall.

limerick_list.author: Ruchiccio
limerick_list.text:
Fifth Avenue boasts Jimmy Choo,
The MoMA and Guggenheim too.
Saks, Tahari, Vuitton,
The Plaza, Cole Haan.
Let's start walking — there's so much to do!

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
I've been hoping my cereals grow,
But their progress seems painfully slow.
While your corn reaches high
As an elephant's eye,
Mine stays low as an elephant's toe.

limerick_list.author: Giri
limerick_list.text:
Someone sneezed in the lift just today.
In a jiffy all moved well away,
And no "bless you" was said
As the gathering fled.
COVID-19 concerns are at play.

limerick_list.author: Rose
limerick_list.text:
"I don't like the river, that's that-o.
Rowing isn't for me." But said Rat, "Oh!
Mole! Don't be a whiner —
There's no pleasure finer
Than messing about in a bateau!"

limerick_list.author: Tim Alborn
limerick_list.text:
A polar bear said, "Howdeedo!"
An Inuit said, "Toodle-oo!"
My trip to the Arctic
Was truly cathartic.
Degrees below zero? A few.

limerick_list.author: skipjordan
limerick_list.text:
Chuck got caught, and they read him his rights.
He copped chips at the place he worked nights.
Memory's gone; he'll see jail
For the theft, on the scale
Of unthinkable billions of bytes.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
As fidei-commissioner, I
Must distribute a part of dad's pie
To a low, bastard brother!
One way or another,
Estate law I'll try to defy!

limerick_list.author: Bob Dvorak
limerick_list.text:
Time for class; as I stepped from the dorm,
Snow was blowing — I tried to keep warm:
Pulled my parka in tight,
Turned the collar up, right
'Gainst the blistery wind of the storm.

limerick_list.author: Celia Warren
limerick_list.text:
It's such fun when we frolic and play,
In the hayloft, in newly-mown hay,
Where no-one will know,
Except horses below,
Until nine short months later, next May ...

limerick_list.author: Peter Meyer
limerick_list.text:
"Meet Perrey," said neighbour Pete Merrey.
"We're having a nice glass of sherry,
And later or sooner
We'll talk about Spooner
Or anagrams rhyming with ferry."

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Chronogrammatists exercise wit.
Their inscriptions are cunningly writ:
Clever wording will hide
A date written inside.
I respect their technique quite a bit.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Last night in our neighborhood diner,
I endured epilepsia minor:
Had a fit—petit mal—
While caressing my gal.
To feel sexy it didn't incline 'er.

limerick_list.author: jayrusalem
limerick_list.text:
The Cyanocitta cristata!
(I'd say syllable-wise, that's a lotta.)
It's much simpler to say
He's the blue jay, okay?
Found mostly on land, not on watta.

limerick_list.author: Steve Ngai
limerick_list.text:
If you stare at a cloudless blue sky,
You will see tiny flashes flit by.
This blue-field entoptic
Phenomenon optic-
ally demonstrates cells in your eye.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Our manager quit with a frown.
Now we're looking all over the town
For a new guy who's, yup,
Quite reserved, buttoned-up,
And conservative, too (buttoned-down).

limerick_list.author: Celia Warren
limerick_list.text:
They are tolling Joe's death knell. Each bong
Of the church bell's as cold as it's long.
We've been hearing that chime
For some weeks. It's high time
That they buried Joe now there's a pong.

limerick_list.author: David Roberts
limerick_list.text:
To emule's to ape, and it might
Be quite nice, or it might be in spite,
Like to mimic in jest
Some buffoon you detest:
To mock or deride as a slight.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
My mechanism for slipping away
From reality faced every day?
It's the gift of the grape.
Yes, through wine I escape,
Keeping life's painful torments at bay.

limerick_list.author: Richard Stehr
limerick_list.text:
It was dairy theft in the extreme;
Clever cats were involved in the scheme.
Detectives spent time
At the scene of the crime,
But there wasn't a sign of the cream.

limerick_list.author: nevadaace
limerick_list.text:
If the spuds that you cook taste like wood
And appear not as nice as they should,
Fetch some tubers and make 'em
Au gratin or bake 'em.
Find Anya potatoes; they're good.

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
I'm a hack, and I'm keeping a tab
On the gypsies who swoop in to grab
Every fare that I'm after,
Then taunt me with laughter.
So yes, you can call me a cab.

limerick_list.author: Mary
limerick_list.text:
I exclaimed, "It is just as I feared:
There's a tree with the name old man's beard,
And Lear's limerick is true,
Though an avian crew
In this fringe tree has not yet appeared."

limerick_list.author: Virge
limerick_list.text:
A mariner, bald and rotund,
Hung around looking senseless and stunned.
He, in place of a cross,
Wore a dead albatross:
That's a sure-fire way to be shunned.

limerick_list.author: Richard English
limerick_list.text:
American, British, Australian,
Canadian too (but no alien).
ABCA as a group —
Though an alphabet soup —
The alternative's sesquipedalian.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
At Alfred, Lord Tennyson's side
At Westminster, you won't find his bride.
But you will see his bust
(It remains there, I trust) —
At the Abbey, things tend to abide.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Teen-aged Abby, my niece, loves to gab,
But she shortens her words.  She says "Fab!"
Meaning "fabulous," but
When I grouse at the cut,
She gets crabby and claims I'm too drab.

limerick_list.author: Dave Jermy
limerick_list.text:
The cops caught a carthorse called Mort,
Who had plugged his pal Prancer for sport.
He was held without hay,
Just one apple a day,
Then was tried at the Badminton court.

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
My pent-up emotions increased
With her nagging.  I had them released
When I blew off some steam
With a loud primal scream.
If I hadn't, she might be deceased.

limerick_list.author: Ulfras
limerick_list.text:
Adulterous people perplex,
Going outside of marriage for sex.
By performing this feat,
One is labeled a cheat
And can often wind up as an ex.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
The life of a farmer?  A breeze!
So I thought till I tried it—puh-leeze!
A fine cash crop is what
I had planned to raise, but
Sadly, money does not grow on trees.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
International finance is funny?
This is more than a strip about money.
What makes Alex a hit?
Dazzling wordplay and wit
Making rainy day forecasts seem sunny.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
All secular pleasures she'll shun:
The cenobite—she is the one
Who's contented to care
For the needy, with prayer,
As she's living the life of a nun.

limerick_list.author: Fringe
limerick_list.text:
East Indian fig trees put out
Aerial shoots that grow downwards, no doubt.
When these reach the ground
Where they grow, safe and sound,
They bring newly grown trunks all about.

limerick_list.author: Meg Beagle
limerick_list.text:
We're keeping things brief at our meeting.
The agenda is short—time is fleeting.
Our chair will be mute,
And his hurry acute.
To urge speed there'll be limited seating.

limerick_list.author: Doug Harris and Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
I had reckoned I could be "the Bard"
Till my progress was suddenly marred
By Shakespearience lacking.
My fans sent me packing.
At last I've succeeded: I'm barred.

limerick_list.author: Chaiwallah
limerick_list.text:
Alas, if to spam you respond,
You create an insoluble bond,
As your email address
Attracts more spam, not less,
From the spamming-hell regions beyond.

limerick_list.author: Robert Holland
limerick_list.text:
When Europe was still in its dawn
At the time of the great Genghis Khan,
There were only fleet horses,
Instead of new Porsches
Ablaze on the roads out of Bonn.

limerick_list.author: proof
limerick_list.text:
Whoa! My brakes don't work. How can that be?
Cool and calm, I must stay, yessiree.
Now to stop this car quick,
What's the best path to pick?
I'll cool-headedly aim at that tree.

limerick_list.author: Kevin
limerick_list.text:
I was quite amused seeing my neighbour
Rather clumsily throwing a sabre.
When I asked, "What is this?"
He replied with a hiss,
"I am practising tossing the caber."

limerick_list.author: Noel Romey
limerick_list.text:
Absorbent material, say,
Can mop egg yolk or spilled cabernet.
But if  left way too long,
Hear the fat lady's song:
"Oh, darn it! That stain's here to stay!"

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
Last night with my beer goggles worn
At the bar, I was drunk.  Coulda sworn
That that woman was hot,
But most certainly not
As I soberly eye her this morn.

limerick_list.author: timon
limerick_list.text:
Does this site not permit erotesis?
Does our data-base show no increases?
Is there here no tradition
Of skilled definition?
(Have I failed to convince of my thesis?)

limerick_list.author: nevadaace
limerick_list.text:
On one's bike if the axle set breaks
A mechanic should not make mistakes.
With cones, washers and nuts,
If he works like a klutz,
When you ride all you'll feel are the shakes.

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
Body snatching's a terrible deed,
So for Grandfather's graveyard, I'll plead
For a watchman who keeps
A close eye on the creeps
Who for bones have a jones and a need.

limerick_list.author: waterrocks
limerick_list.text:
The colon: a beautiful mark.
Neatly balanced; no squiggles: how stark!
Its message is: "Hey!
Here it comes: what I say
Follows on: you're not left in the dark."

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
My dear friend, my good buddy, my bruvver,
Was hoping I'd never discover
The  reason he's dead
And now filled full of lead:
That he'd taken my wife as his lover.

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
The grysbok is small, brownish-red,
Has short, vertical horns on its head,
And is mainly nocturnal,
I wrote in my journal
In African Antelope Ed.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
When I gaze up at night at the moon,
On a cool, lovely evening in June,
Though it sounds pedagogical,
My heart's aerological:
I pine for a weather balloon.

limerick_list.author: AndrewB
limerick_list.text:
We divide the world's people in two:
There are us, and of course all of you.
Oh, we might call them goys,
Those uncircumcised boys.
You're a gentile if you're not a Jew.

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
My novel's adjudged a success—
By a publishing outfit, no less!
It's considered so good
I think everyone should
Buy a copy from Vanity Press.

limerick_list.author: lopey
limerick_list.text:
An air dam is like a big scoop
That's placed underneath your old coupe.
It reroutes the air's flow—
Cools the engine, you know,
And prevents you from flipping a loop.

limerick_list.author: rusty
limerick_list.text:
"Just do it!" is so fitspirational.
"Sweat more and bitch less" — motivational!
I love "Let go of doubt".
Slogans beat workin' out!
(Can't work out why my flab's so stagnational.)

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
My math teacher thinks it's a hoot
To insist that we take the square root
Of a negative number—
But what could be dumber
Than a value that i can't compute?

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
My friend Tinker Bell can't help but drink.
So eupeptic, was I  — tickled pink  —
When she stayed on the wagon
And off of the flagon:
Two shot-glasses? One pickled Tink.

limerick_list.author: Dr. Work
limerick_list.text:
"I would like to be vegan," claimed Roy.
But an antianemia ploy
Was his pretext to eat
His daily red meat—
Though I bet he's just tired of soy.

limerick_list.author: Recumbentman
limerick_list.text:
Apocryphalness is the state
Of Utopia, Erewhon, Great
Expectations, and Tobit;
It means they have no bit
Of credit marked up on their slate.

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
For a gal, it's a shoe with a strap,
And a sock, kinda short, for a chap.
It's an ornament worn
On the leg to adorn.
So they're anklets, all three. That's a wrap!

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
Allow copper its pros and its cons,
But its use as a tool corresponds
To a period mythic:
The Aeneolithic,
Which led to the age we call Bronze.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
The advice ante cibum conceals
What a knowledge of Latin reveals.
With your pills, this is key:
The Rx says a.c.?
That's a shorthand for "take before meals."

limerick_list.author: Janet McConnaughey
