limerick_list.text:
"O mine host, I've a toast. Let me think …
To the host with the most!" (Glasses clink.)
"If you'll not pull the plug,
I'll engage now to chug
A full gage." (That's a quart pot of drink.)

limerick_list.author: mrsrev
limerick_list.text:
The bubbles had all gone away,
'Cause my bathtub was leaking that day.
So I went down to buy
(After I had got dry)
Some more caulking so water would stay.

limerick_list.author: Charles Silliman
limerick_list.text:
It's my favorite place to go eat.
Nice decor with great service — complete.
They serve tasty, digestible,
Healthy, comestible
Items with flair — what a treat!

limerick_list.author: AndrewB
limerick_list.text:
When I file a complaint in a court,
I might claim breach of contract  or tort.
This is not when I show
All my evidence, though.
At the trial, you'll see my support.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
I've engaged your great-grandfather's stein
For your fifty-buck loan, so don't whine.
When the note becomes due
Just repay me, then you
Get it back, but if not it's all mine.

limerick_list.author: Charles Silliman
limerick_list.text:
Every land-lubbin' captive aboard
Heard the rum-inspired pirate who roared,
"Ye abhorred stinking dumb
Scurvy scallywag scum,
Walk the plank, or it's death by me sword!"

limerick_list.author: Michael Toalster and SusanL
limerick_list.text:
Assistive technologies seek
To help people whose lives may seem bleak,
Since their bodies are not
What the rest of us got
When we were all given physique.

limerick_list.author: David
limerick_list.text:
Once a thirty-foot Amazon boa
Surprised a poor chicle tree groa.
He got stuck to his tree,
So could only shriek, "Eeee!"
And now the poor groa's no moa.

limerick_list.author: Goldie
limerick_list.text:
The machine-gunning crook Al Capone
On Chicago's south side set the tone.
"I will never confess —
Not to Eliot Ness."
So he said.  Then his cover was blown.

limerick_list.author: Jeff Foster
limerick_list.text:
A thirsty trombonist named Rhoda
Was dreaming of frosty cream soda
And missed the dal segno.
Cried Maestro in pain, "Yo!
Go back to the sign, not the coda!"

limerick_list.author: JimInRoses
limerick_list.text:
Concluding, I want you to know
It's been great, and I'm sorry to go.
But the room will be dark
Ere my closing remark
If you don't come across with the dough.

limerick_list.author: Mary
limerick_list.text:
Plant a cover crop; build up the soil.
Adding nitrogen, clover will foil
Most erosion and bring
Crimson beauty in spring:
Beneficial delights—little toil!

limerick_list.author: CruzerX
limerick_list.text:
The brain trust that runs our division
Likes to manage by threat and derision.
They're the stockholder's whores
And they're planning new scores
While they screw us by corporate decision.

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
Yet again, my computer just shut off,
Leaving downtime from working my butt off.
While it's fixed, I relax,
Maybe have a few snacks.
Now I notice I must work my gut off.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
"Where's Timothy gone? That's the question."
"Down two throats, at a buddy's suggestion."
Seems he wrongly depended
On cavers he'd friended.
Hope he gave those false friends indigestion.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Said the vulture, "I fear folks will mark us
When they see how dead animals spark us
Into noisy disputes.
They'll consider us brutes
If we're quibbling while nibbling a carcass."

limerick_list.author: Mark Mironer
limerick_list.text:
Bodewash's odd root's understood:
Bois de vache (from the French for "cow's wood").
Dried buffalo dung—
On the fire it's flung.
Those buffalo chips sure are good!

limerick_list.author: Sussexdownsman
limerick_list.text:
Apiculturists seldom just die.
When the Grim Reaper calls, they reply:
"Don't be funny, it's sunny
And honey makes money.
Just buzz off yourself, bearded guy!"

limerick_list.author: Michael Toalster
limerick_list.text:
The two of us make a fine pair.
But we'd better look out and take care:
New dangers may wait
Behind every new gate,
Any time, any place, anywhere.

limerick_list.author: johng
limerick_list.text:
I swam in a bath full of cream,
And that's when I started to scream.
For there in the dark,
I encountered a shark...
I awoke—it was only a dream!

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
His command of the court's not in doubt;
It's a clinic each time he goes out.
You will never forget
His great play at the net.
He's what tennis today is about.

limerick_list.author: creelbm
limerick_list.text:
During Sesame Street's starting spiel
Are shown donors both quirky and real.
It's a kid-centric crew,
Such as "Viewers Like You".
Pampers, C, and fifteen are ideal.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
If you're out for a ride, one fine day,
In a cab called a cabriolet,
You'll have only one horse,
And a carriage, of course—
Just two wheels, but a lot of cachet.

limerick_list.author: Jane Auerbach
limerick_list.text:
The buck, said the prez, stops right here:
On the president's desk (or quite near).
Now, the schmuck's out of luck
Who went bang!  for the buck,
'Cause his prank caused the White House to clear.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere and JimInRoses
limerick_list.text:
Crucifixion was painful and gory,
As four told, and retold, in His story:
Matthew, Mark, Luke and John—
Passing on the baton—
The Evangelists spreading the glory.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
With Livia, Vivie must divvy a
Cash prize from a quiz based on trivia:
Candomblé dance? A samba.
Right. What's Cochabamba?
A city in Central Bolivia!

limerick_list.author: CaptainLex
limerick_list.text:
To desacralize things, I regret,
Makes traditional clergy upset.
When a relic or thought
Goes from holy to not,
They suspect it's a secular threat.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
Your gallantry, sir, has no bound;
Though that courtliness stuff, I have found,
In seducers like you
Has a good deal to do
With the fact I've young daughters around.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
"His review of my dance made me burn!"
Said the Soviet dancer named Fern.
"To his comrades, I'll bet,
He panned my pirouette,
And he called it a cheap common turn."

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
South American nightclubs are where
You might meet a large rodent with flair.
He appears, in a cage,
Doing Charo on stage.
("Cuchi-cuchi" acouchies are rare!)

limerick_list.author: JimInRoses
limerick_list.text:
Twin babies! I'm proud of their growth,
But one's starting to look like a sloth.
That change, developmental,
Is just coincidental,
And doesn't apply to them both.

limerick_list.author: Taillefer
limerick_list.text:
On a field day, they're out in the yard 'n'
Play football? I do beg your pardon!
All the "field days" I had
Were imposed by my dad
And meant nothing but work in his garden.

limerick_list.author: GeneralE
limerick_list.text:
O'er the Baltic, ships Seaslessly rolled,
And the Latvian sailors were bold.
The Estonians, too,
With Lithuanians who
Formed some States in a war which was cold.

limerick_list.author: David Roberts
limerick_list.text:
For his god, yet another man dies,
Reckless hate for my soul in his eyes.
Is it asking a smidgeon
Too much of religion
To depolarize those who despise?

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
'Til enrolling in cookery class,
All your cooking had tasted like ass.
Now your great-tasting beans,
Based on vegan cuisines,
Mean you're finally cooking with gas!

limerick_list.author: Ulfras
limerick_list.text:
With houseplants I'm really quite dumb,
Having never possessed a green thumb.
But with just air to nourish
Them aerials flourish—
Even I cannot make them succumb.

limerick_list.author: nevadaace
limerick_list.text:
Abdominal (wheeze) respiration
Is your diaphragm's chief occupation.
If (wheeze)  you're exhaling
And feel your lungs failing,
Get (wheeze)  some good (wheeze)  medication.

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
At Christmastime, crowds are abustle
With shoppers who busily hustle.
But good cheer goes awry
With the latest must-buy
When the limited stocks cause a tussle.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
We would do it just twice: once at night,
And again as the morning turned bright.
Then we heard a great song
That explained we were wrong —
Afternoon is just right for delight!

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
The eagle's a powerful raptor,
To our lifestyle a clever adapter.
Near its nest you reside?
Keep your dachshund inside,
Or you'll find that an eagle's its captor.

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
The countrified fare that I'm pickin'
Is a helping of country fried chicken.
But your citified dish
Doesn't look so delish:
Is that rat still alive? . . . Look, it's kickin'!

limerick_list.author: rusty
limerick_list.text:
No, my gal, you don't fly your own jet,
And no shih-tzu is yours for a pet.
It's hard farmwork all day,
Rain or shine, come what may.
Then we roll in the hay, farmerette.

limerick_list.author: psheil
limerick_list.text:
Oh Mother, please come help me quick!
My stomach on me plays a trick.
I'm sorely afraid
That my food will abraid:
In this green, pleasant glade I'll be s...

limerick_list.author: JimInRoses
limerick_list.text:
A contractive appendage will shrink —
Maybe more than you'd possibly think.
The reverse of this show
Is that, first, it must grow.
If you saw it, I know you would blink.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
She insisted on fiddleback oak
For our floors, but the cost was no joke.
"It's got fabulous grain,"
She cooed. "Hon, don't complain."
She's persuasive; I folded; we're broke.

limerick_list.author: Jean McEwen
limerick_list.text:
The society's board of trustees
Has approved the festoons for the frieze:
A floral design
With flower and vine—
An encarpus with style sure to please.

limerick_list.author: Len Farano
limerick_list.text:
"I'm not sure whether I can stay strong,"
Yogi sobbed as he spoke to the throng.
"I feel so bereft
Now that Boo Boo has left."
He said, "Bearably, I'll get along."

limerick_list.author: rusty
limerick_list.text:
He ensorcels us—now we're resourceless.
When he casts evil spells, we're recourseless.
His magical work'll
Cause flames to encircle.
This sorcerer's force is remorseless.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
I delight in my neighbors' bravado—
Each a football afficionado.
Coloradans are they?
Coloradoans? Hey!
Just the folks from our state—Colorado.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
The abature's only the traces
A stag leaves behind as he races
Through woods unconfined,
Leaving hunters behind,
As he leads them on long fruitless chases.

limerick_list.author: splendiferous
limerick_list.text:
This clamor is cause for vexation,
An entomologic frustration.
The buzzing, it seems,
Has invaded my dreams
And explodes in my ears: bombination.

limerick_list.author: psheil
limerick_list.text:
A sentence that's complex has clauses
Conjoined by conjunctions — and pauses —
But, dear reader, take care,
Hidden dangers lurk there;
Complex diction now causes locked-jawses.

limerick_list.author: JimInRoses
limerick_list.text:
Religions have myths of Creation:
Our Earth's and its people's formation,
Ordained by a deity.
God's spontaneity
Suffers a lot in translation.

limerick_list.author: Janet McConnaughey
limerick_list.text:
As I nibble away at my strudel,
I think of my in-laws, their poodle,
And my wife's younger brothers.
If I had my druthers,
They'd all move away, the whole boodle.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
The once-savvy teacher was flustered.
He hemmed, and he hawed, and he blustered.
He'd forgotten his chalk,
Lost the thread of his talk—
He can't cut it. He can't cut the mustard!

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
His utopia came in our sleep.
Now his words I recall: "Creep by creep,
Going steady and slow,
We'll take baby steps."  Though,
Looking back, we took one giant leap.

limerick_list.author: DBRHoffman and Snowy Owl
limerick_list.text:
In the age of the glory of Greece,
If you're captured for killing your niece,
You'll soon see the Archon
Basileus's mark on
The order to jail or release.

limerick_list.author: Jane Auerbach
limerick_list.text:
My contractor's subs use bad crews,
Shoddy workers I'd never once choose.
I'm so mad I could scream
At their wiring scheme—
Electricians who just blew my fuse.

limerick_list.author: GeneralE
limerick_list.text:
Begin with a zero or one,
Add commands and you start to have fun.
Start defining a rule —
I  think if/else is cool —
Compile, and you're basically done.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
A scheduling conflict's a pain:
For my barbecue, God scheduled rain,
So I chose a new date;
Bad idea, tempting fate—
An earthquake! God's yanking my chain.

limerick_list.author: Jim Vincent
limerick_list.text:
You grew up without gratitude showing—
No danke, merci ever flowing.
We gave, and you took
(As if some kind of crook).
Now you're leaving, still thank-you forgoing.

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
Our daughters behave and excel,
While our sons often put us through hell.
We don't coddle the males,
But just paddle their tails,
Since a caudal shellacking works well.

limerick_list.author: Jane Auerbach
limerick_list.text:
An abbot inhabits an abbey;
He's the boss of the place—not too shabby.
He goes by one name,
And his monks would proclaim
He's devoted, devout, and not gabby.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Sue's spouse Len spent six days on a  bender.
"Sure he's sick, but you too need a mender,"
Said an Al-Anon friend
To Len's wife. In the end,
It was Sue who was first to surrender.

limerick_list.author: Chris Young
limerick_list.text:
If you value at 3 this parameter —
Column gap over column diameter —
Then your porch, bay or aisle
Is styled diastyle style.
Limerick done; next, iambic pentameter...

limerick_list.author: Roger Dunn
limerick_list.text:
I reflect on my back, should it ache,
And give thought to my nails, if they break,
But the way I behave'll
Adjust when my navel
I contemplate: soul-searchings make.

limerick_list.author: Engineer
limerick_list.text:
At the church of St. Stephen, I creep
Down the aisle, making nary a peep,
When I spy on the right
Such a Gothic delight:
An acute arch quite narrow and steep.

limerick_list.author: Richard Stehr
limerick_list.text:
Cataloger—now what could that be?
One who catalogs things, you'd agree.
But the way the word sounds,
Those who hear it have grounds
To think: beer that is brewed from cow's pee.

limerick_list.author: J. E. Pettit
limerick_list.text:
While in class, I become catatonic
If the talk turns to things baryonic
(That is, everyday matter).
But dodging such chatter
Is easy: I claim I'm dysphonic.

limerick_list.author: Mary
limerick_list.text:
Epilobium canum, it's said,
Is the hummingbird flower. Though deer tread
Near its foliage, it's stout,
And it tolerates drought.
(There's a cultivar named 'Ghostly Red'.)

limerick_list.author: R. A. Shortfellow
limerick_list.text:
Mother Nature a rock will demolish,
Though the fragments she won't quite abolish.
Heat and cold, winds and rains,
Break it up — the remains?
Called eluvium: pieces quite smallish.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
This torture room's ugly; it's hurtin'.
We can fix it in no time, I'm certain.
I know what it lacks:
We must spray-paint the racks,
And the waterboard clinic becurtain.

limerick_list.author: Chuck Folkers
limerick_list.text:
To make plywood with knotholes omitted,
The layer on top must be slitted;
The almond-shaped space
You cut out is the place
Where a boat patch is carefully fitted.

limerick_list.author: SusanL
limerick_list.text:
How could you become so remiss?
Did you think you'd found heavenly bliss?
Now your life's on display,
And you're sure gonna pay—
There is bound to be fallout from this.

limerick_list.author: C. H. Carpenter
limerick_list.text:
One must catalog books with respect
To the subjects they clearly reflect,
Since the headings will lead
Searching patrons to heed
Needed books they might elsewise neglect.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
We're a-settin' around, chunkin' stones,
And a-ponderin' life's great unknowns,
Like why's throwin' this stuff
To hit frogs so dang tough—
And the wonders of Emmaline Jones.

limerick_list.author: timon
limerick_list.text:
You can trust to the oak and the ash;
Ophelia though was more rash.
Aslant the deep brook,
A crack willow she took
As support for her garland; then…

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
When products cost less, we rejoice.
When they're costless, we're faced with a choice.
I've been offered a car
Free of charge—can't go far
In an engineless, wheelless Rolls-Royce.

limerick_list.author: Recumbentman
limerick_list.text:
We cyclists frequently flout laws,
But it must be conceded about laws:
If they do not protect,
They invite disrespect.
We become, without wanting to, outlaws.

limerick_list.author: Val
limerick_list.text:
Feeling down? She'll drop all to attend,
And a listening ear she will lend,
Plus a shoulder to cry on.
The one you rely on
In good times and bad is a friend.

limerick_list.author: SusanL and Michael Toalster
limerick_list.text:
Our students are idle each summer;
I'm afraid they are all getting dummer.
So let's hire an amuser—
Their teacher should choose her—
Having fun shouldn't make them grow nummer.

limerick_list.author: Chaiwallah
limerick_list.text:
King Henry was shrewd, mathematical,
In dealing with profits abbatical.
He said, "These palatial
Estates aren't abbatial:
The abbots are far too fanatical."

limerick_list.author: Chris Young
limerick_list.text:
In my embryo sac, there's a twin.
As a flower, new life will begin
Since a pollen-grain's sperm
And my egg made the germ
Of a seed — which has endosperm kin...

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Mom objects to my talking in slang,
But I want to be one of the gang—
So I say what I like.
She can go take a hike,
As the truth is I don't care a hang!

limerick_list.author: Goldie
limerick_list.text:
Got purple?  Got yellow?  Got gray?
Get your color filters — buy some today!
Glass or gelatin, dyed,
They're designed to provide
All the hues that you want to portray!

limerick_list.author: Type A
limerick_list.text:
In Rome in Augustus's day,
Playing ball in the house was okay.
Since its inner décor
Had no roof—just a floor,
In these atriums children could play.

limerick_list.author: ironmike
limerick_list.text:
ABIOS is BIOS enhanced.
It is firmware that's truly advanced.
In ROM it resides
As nimbly it guides
A computer to get up and dance.

limerick_list.author: Bill Cernansky
limerick_list.text:
On the dark web a botmaster hides,
While surveilling the bots that he guides.
He's promoting a meme
That will further his scheme
To claim Russia's where Elvis resides.

limerick_list.author: Kalleh
limerick_list.text:
There once was a woman named Blake
Who complained that her stomach did ache.
The doctor came quickly,
Pronouncing her "sickly."
She really was quite a good fake!

limerick_list.author: Val
limerick_list.text:
What is Time?  Can it pause or do shunts?
Well, on that, I confess, I'm a dunce.
Though it does seem to me
Time is so we can be
And stops everything happening at once.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Cotemporary?  Read the word fast,
And it sounds like our love cannot last,
But cotemporaneous?
My response, instantaneous:
"We're concurrent." Impressions contrast!

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
The mood in our office was stressed,
So the corporate concierge did his best:
Had appointments arranged,
Had our rejects exchanged.
Our spouses were duly impressed.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
To befog is to render unclear.
It's to obfuscate, muddy, or smear,
To bedim or to screen
What one doesn't want seen,
To becloud, or to make disappear.

limerick_list.author: BobfromThirsk
limerick_list.text:
Buy 'em 'ere, it's a sure way to thrift:
Pay me cash, no receipt, catch my drift?
What's that! "Stolen bloomers"?!
Who's spreading these rumours?
They're lovely, they're silk, they're a gift.

limerick_list.author: Errol Nimbly
limerick_list.text:
Heed my ax, which is dubbed double-bitted;
With a double-edged blade it is fitted.
It can fell mighty trees,
Or bring men to their knees
When it's swung that their skulls shall be splitted.

limerick_list.author: stella
limerick_list.text:
Connochaetes, or gnus, Susie knew,
Could be black-hued or brindled (or blue),
But if black gnus are kindled
By blue gnus (or brindled),
Sue's clueless what hues will ensue.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Our goal is a stout that is brewable
So dark and so thick that it's chewable.
When the going gets rough,
Will hard work be enough?
Yes! The job may be tough, but it's doable.

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
Paying cash on the barrelhead, Darryl
Bought the enterprise—lock, stock, and barrel.
Now he's barely begun
Having barrels of fun,
Selling barrels of Darryl's apparel.

limerick_list.author: a.groovymind
limerick_list.text:
Well now, Chico's a place, to be sure,
Though for me not a spot with allure.
But the Chico who harks
From the three brothers Marx?
He's, ah, giving-a pleasure that's pure.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
When our church was complete, we could tell
That the south wall was dodgy as hell.
Brother Boris built for us
A stout abamurus;
It's standing, but don't ring the bell.

limerick_list.author: lopey and Snowy Owl
limerick_list.text:
Anarchism's simply explained,
But to many, the term has been stained.
So for those who'd rebel,
Here's the meaning I'd tell:
Interactions should not be constrained.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Deb is sweet and outgoing and kind
And upbeat (a remarkable find!),
So it's sad to convey
I discovered today
She's congenially robbing me blind.

limerick_list.author: Chris Young
limerick_list.text:
The skin which my razor blades slish'll
Soon heal; the result's cicatricial.
With my arms marked and marred,
I'm aesthetically scarred.
(You must suffer for Art; that's official.)

limerick_list.author: R. A. Shortfellow
limerick_list.text:
Ever since we put engines on carts,
We've had brake drums as requisite parts.
Don't maintain them? All's lost,
And brake failure's the cost:
Can't stop; you might crash; panic starts.

limerick_list.author: limarico
limerick_list.text:
I can't drink this water. Its drinkableness
Is like that of piss. The unthinkableness
Of tasting this swill
Makes me retch and grow ill.
So I'll dump it. Thank God for its sinkableness.

limerick_list.author: speedysnail
limerick_list.text:
In imperial days, we called Britain
The island where greatness was written.
As many have grumbled,
The Empire has crumbled—
It's here in the damp we're left sittin'.

limerick_list.author: Len Farano
limerick_list.text:
It's so sad that we must close the book
On a hero fans called "Captain Hook".
Baseball's "Sparky" has passed,
But the wins he amassed
Proved he gave so much more than he took.

limerick_list.author: JimInRoses
limerick_list.text:
Though I know I'm not pretty or clever,
I've a man who will love me for ever.
Or at least so he said
As we climbed into bed…
Disbelievingly, Mother said, "Never!"

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Your website I'm trying to hack
By employing a dictionary attack.
What's your password? Don't know,
So instead I will go
Through an A to Z list front to back.

limerick_list.author: BobfromThirsk
limerick_list.text:
Playing cricket, a bowler named Grout
Liked to aim, high and hard, at one's snout.
Hear it whizz—it's a screamer!
It's known as a beamer.
Not out! But a knockout for nowt.

limerick_list.author: Roger Vick
limerick_list.text:
Croaking multiple songs, the noise crested:
A beau geste to suggest life's congested.
Such deception may pay,
Keeping rivals at bay:
The male tree frog's domain uncontested.

limerick_list.author: Thomas Taylor
limerick_list.text:
For his toothache, Philandering Merv
Applied clove oil to deaden the nerve.
Those botanical drops
Made him numb in the chops,
But they helped get his mind back to 'luurv'.

limerick_list.author: David
limerick_list.text:
If you hear eerie howls that seem floaty
In moonlight, perhaps, or just throaty,
It's surely a brush wolf
At whom you shout, "Shush, wolf!"
Or, "Can it, you crazy coyote!"

limerick_list.author: AlexiConn
limerick_list.text:
My dear husband, I'd like to assist
With your chores so I've made you a list.
For each task that you lick
Mark it off with a tick
To be certain that nothing is missed.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
I am sure I will never forget
When I first got to use a curette.
While removing the tumor,
I tried to use humor,
And bombed, to my lasting regret.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
A salsa musician named Mario
Became a renowned impresario.
He is famous worldwide
Where Latinos reside,
So they call him the "King of the Barrio."

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
A borate's identification
Depends on its state of hydration;
It has B2O3
Plus hydroxide, you see,
And a cation's neutralization.

limerick_list.author: Sussexdownsman
limerick_list.text:
A nice college boy wanted to date a
Post grad, but was tied to his mater.
Said the woman, "It's sad,
You've a complex, real bad!
I'm afreud you're too jung, come back later."

limerick_list.author: BobHale
limerick_list.text:
In the bar where the fishermen chat,
With his arms spread wide open, old Pat
Said, "'Twas this big. Alack,
That I threw the thing back."
(But he lied. 'Twas no more than a sprat.)

limerick_list.author: squid_shirt
limerick_list.text:
As I hungrily sit at my bench,
I ponder my food while I quench:
"If it's  à l'espagnole
In this Spanish-style bowl,
Then why would you name it in French?"

limerick_list.author: Seth Brown
limerick_list.text:
For a mapped Human Genome mosaic,
We'll need formulas writ algebraic.
 One can hardly be placid
 While adding up acid
That's deoxyribonucleic.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
A Japanese beetle named Sy,
Not too high in the sky, by my eye,
My swipe notwithstanding,
Had passed without landing,
A fly by ("Banzai!") then bye-bye.

limerick_list.author: proof
limerick_list.text:
Using cut-outs once got out of hand,
So the Postmaster said, "We demand
You don't paste stamps you're cutting
On letters to Nutting.
Attention! This practice is banned."

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
Our boat's sprung a leak.  Tempest-tossed,
It could sink any time — we'd be lost.
I pray fervently, though,
That my bro from Bordeaux
With a tow isn't slow. Fingers crossed!

limerick_list.author: hugh t.
limerick_list.text:
Each time Trajan had just won a war,
He built an arch, marking his score;
But researches archival
Show he had an arch-rival:
Augustus erected still more.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
"An accessory breast? Like a purse?"
"No, when women have triplets to nurse,
This additional breast
Might be found on her chest,
On her back, or perhaps somewhere worse."

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
Ancient (Archae) bird (orni) form (thoidies)
It's a name that's among longer woidies.
From a fossilized head,
One thing certain is said:
Archie's one of the smallest old boidies.

limerick_list.author: hugh.adler
limerick_list.text:
One who drinks 'til he falls to the floor,
Or an angling device, like a lure?
No—to me, the word chugger
Means "charity mugger",
A bloke you'd be wise to ignore.

limerick_list.author: Doug Aldridge
limerick_list.text:
My barber cuts hair very well,
But I'm balding so much I would tell
Him I want a cost break
('Cause, how long can it take?)
But he'd say, "It's the search that's pure hell!"

limerick_list.author: David
limerick_list.text:
A confirmed vegetarian, I
Must acknowledge that boerewors (sigh)
Used to smell and taste good,
As spiced sausages should,
At an Afrikaans barbecue (braai).

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Charactonyms? I think they rock!
They're devices that writers won't knock.
There are instances ample:
Disney's dwarfs, for example
(Though, technically speaking, not Doc).

limerick_list.author: Len Farano
limerick_list.text:
They're called "madmen" and often maligned
When their visions cannot be defined
Within norms that we know.
They upset status quo.
To a dark-house they once were consigned.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Uncle Stan had a quirky demand:
"Use elastic," he'd say. "Understand?
On this term I insist.
I will give you my fist
Should you utter the words rubber band."

limerick_list.author: rusty
limerick_list.text:
Learnt from London's Great Fire, endurance.
From its ashes, he built, earning new rents.
There's gold in that carbon,
Knew Nicholas Barbon,
Inventor of fire insurance.

limerick_list.author: skipjordan
limerick_list.text:
Please dishaunt us, dear ghost; I'm a sight!
I can't sleep, and my bloke and I fight.
We are tired of your bells
And those musty old smells,
And strange things that go bump in the night.

limerick_list.author: MikeAq
limerick_list.text:
When told Heaven has all kinds of perks
(Plus without being saved, Hades lurks!),
I did all the math,
Was baptized in a bath —
Renounced Satan and all of his works.

limerick_list.author: jojo
limerick_list.text:
An old bear in a forest near Oslo
Brings Lars (with a swipe of his paws) low,
But breaks teeth 'cause Lars' chest
Sports a Kevlar-lined vest.
On Lars' softer parts Bruin now gnaws slow.

limerick_list.author: HeuristicsInc
limerick_list.text:
Atmospheric-type pressure should be
Based on Earth's, which is 1 by decree.
It's the weight of the air,
Or whatever is there —
So on Pluto it's point oh oh three.

limerick_list.author: zqms
limerick_list.text:
At the blackboard, in physics, Mike shows
Ways how current electricity flows:
"Charged electrons zip round.
(Also protons, I've found.)
As to why: I'm afraid no one knows."

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
"Our concert's been cancelled," said Tom,
Unperturbed and with nary a qualm.
Since that circumstance meant
That we can't pay our rent,
He appeared disconcertingly calm.

limerick_list.author: proof
limerick_list.text:
While they're damp, I toss clothes in the dryer,
Set the dial on high, then one higher.
They're all done when you choke
On the billowing smoke
And can't open the door — too much fire.

limerick_list.author: mike scholtes
limerick_list.text:
I, with darkroom technology buy-in,
Shine yellow, magenta, and cyan
With a head that's dichroic.
Seems paleozoic?
This craft, I will silver and dye in!

limerick_list.author: StephenGold
limerick_list.text:
I am in the environs of Myron,
A locality less than inspirin'.
So hard is the labour
In bein' his neighbour,
I'm desirin' of swiftly expirin'.

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
He deserves telling off, but he's scary.
I know just what to do: send for Mary.
Yes, big Mary—the fat one.
She's a fire-eater, that one,
And ornery, loud and contrary.

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
"You'll take pro, I'll take con. Then you'll gratingly
Argue your points, but frustratingly
Not choose to fish
Or cut bait, and just pish
At my brilliance," said Thomas debatingly.

limerick_list.author: PGS
limerick_list.text:
A professional organization
Serves American high education:
Clearly civilly based
Engineers are well placed
In this dignified, aged formation.

limerick_list.author: CruzerX
limerick_list.text:
Ancient Colchis, the end of the world
For the Argonauts destiny's hurled
Famous heroes of old:
Led by Jason the Bold
As they sailed o'er the ocean so purled.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
What's a dishclout? A powerful hit
By a plate that's been thrown in a fit?
No,  a cloth to wash dishes
After meals—fish or knishes.
In the kitchen the dishrag won't quit.

limerick_list.author: Roger Vick
limerick_list.text:
She sought jewellery in a boutique:
Found a choker with flair and mystique.
It would serve to bedeck
Granny's scrawny, old neck.
But the price? Ouch! It must be antique.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
When our ancestors felt the vibration
Of the earth—its abrupt agitation—
Cavemen cringed and were scared;
They were never prepared
For an earthquake—the ground's concussation.

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
To the smelliest fellows give thanks
For the stenches in trenches and tanks.
But in cavalry forces,
The sources are horses—
The reason it reeks in the ranks.

limerick_list.author: PGS
limerick_list.text:
Is "empirical" antitheoretical?
This question I pose is poetical,
But there's nothing as good
As a theory we could
Put in practice—not just hypothetical.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Lucy loves to get wild a great deal,
Like at parties her clothing she'll peel.
Uninhibited, gay,
Full of life—her friends say,
"Just get down with your bad self, Lucille!"

limerick_list.author: zqms
limerick_list.text:
My mate Bruce is a boatie; that's why
He said, "Sheila, join in, don't be shy:
Even you can afford
Recreation aboard
A small boat of your own, love. Just try!"

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
A medieval conventional code,
Courtly love set the rules of the road:
What a lady could do,
And what things were taboo,
Whether wooed by a prince or a toad.

limerick_list.author: zqms
limerick_list.text:
It's good form to say "thank you" and "please";
Use a handkerchief, too, when you sneeze.
Raise your hat when we meet,
Just like now, in the street —
And do not give my bottom a squeeze.

limerick_list.author: Tim Alborn
limerick_list.text:
My dinner for two? A fiasco!
The lilies I picked (atamasco)—
All purple and white,
A most beautiful sight!—
Were consumed by my date, with tabasco.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
Screamed the front of Belize's main paper:
"The Case of the Stolen Baird's Tapir!"
As a burger disguised
And a malt, super-sized,
It was smuggled to Spain. Quite the caper!

limerick_list.author: Cuttlefish
limerick_list.text:
When just the right compounds unite
The result is no heat, but bright light.
A firefly's quintessence
Is chemiluminescence—
A magical midsummer sight.

limerick_list.author: Dottie
limerick_list.text:
A very fat lady from Pinner
Declared she would like to be thinner;
But no banting took place,
For she just couldn't face
Eating less than four courses for dinner.

limerick_list.author: proof
limerick_list.text:
A bunker (BOOM!) buster destroys
All the space a dictator enjoys.
Concrete rooms underground
Can no longer be found
Once this laser-aimed missile deploys.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Colles' fracture involves just the radius.
Like a squid who has broken its gladius,
I've no right to complain.
It will heal up again—
Not like Wayne who has (gulp) hypospadias.

limerick_list.author: Roger Vick and Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
A bisexual blooms with its pieces,
Both female and male. That increases
The chance for some seed
To succeed,  and indeed,
See some viable seedy releases.

limerick_list.author: proof
limerick_list.text:
A decipherer's challenged to take
An unreadable code and to make
It a readable text,
But they sometimes are vexed
By a message they just cannot break.

limerick_list.author: Aliza
limerick_list.text:
With her bloodstains on hands and on soul,
This Macbeth is not mentally whole.
Though the lady shouts "Out!"
The damned spot is too stout.
Ere too long she will pay evil's toll.

limerick_list.author: Joanna Keene
limerick_list.text:
GM recalls cars, quite a lot,
To fix defects these autos have got.
They're recalling so many
That Ma said to Kenny,
"Just tell me which cars they are not."

limerick_list.author: Atticus Vere
limerick_list.text:
Lent's behind us; it's Eastering time
At the club, where the pickings are prime:
A whole night petting bunnies,
Those cotton-tailed honeys.
Going pagan's no sin. It's sublime.

limerick_list.author: Mark Mironer
limerick_list.text:
The clinic director was floored
By the two grateful gifts from the board.
"Your section's outstanding,
So plan on expanding —
Accept both our grant and award."

limerick_list.author: Scott Campisi
limerick_list.text:
The authoritarian way
Says that my word is law. Now obey!
Some will call me a bully,
Opposing me fully,
But why should I care what they say?

limerick_list.author: mephistopheles
limerick_list.text:
When you purchase a 'zine, you should brace
As reply cards come tumbling apace.
And they'd surely confuse—
There's too many to use
As a bookmark for holding your place.

limerick_list.author: proof
limerick_list.text:
My pirate friends always have said
Tales aren't told if the teller is dead.
So I'll bury my gold;
Where it's hid won't  be told
'Cause I'm shooting myself in the head.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
Said my friend, who is ever the smarty,
With a sense of himself that is hearty,
"A political cataclysm
Would spring from my radicalism!"
...He joined the Republican Party.

limerick_list.author: sallycello
limerick_list.text:
With no contract, the deal he affirms;
"You can trust me," he says as he squirms.
Though it might seem unjust,
The words lawyer and  trust
Are a clear contradiction in terms.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
"Botheration!" The high price of gas
Troubles Gram, yet that lady has class.
Botherations like these
Earn that label since she's
Too polite to say "pains in the ass."

limerick_list.author: Carol June Hooker
limerick_list.text:
When the lilting of spring fills the world,
Up pops cinnamon fern, tightly furled;
Violin-like its neck.
These we pick by the peck.
In a fiddlehead stir-fry they're swirled.

limerick_list.author: Chris J. Strolin
limerick_list.text:
That was bubbleheaded! Witless! Unwise!
For worst ad pitch, you sure take the prize.
You can quit now your urgin'
We hire a virgin
To promote Grandma Pat's Cherry Pies.

limerick_list.author: psheil
limerick_list.text:
A hundredweight, cwt,
Is one hundred and twelve pounds to me,
But America's weight
Is one hundred pounds, straight;
Just one more thing where we disagree.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
From this perch he would often project
Those directions that brought him respect.
This director's chair, sad,
Now is empty—too bad!
We extol him; we mourn; we reflect.

limerick_list.author: S. A. McBurnie
limerick_list.text:
Though amoebas inside may offend,
Our amoebocytes help to defend.
They're our blood cells in white
And intruders they fight—
But just how do they tell foe from friend?

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
You're determined to sell me some stock?
Please arrive about seven o'clock.
North on Fourth, then turn right
At the red blinking light.
Mine's the eastmost (last) house on the block.

limerick_list.author: rusty
limerick_list.text:
Spread the word! Stick it up on a hoarding, too.
You know, it is warmly rewarding to
Go forth and define
This old term (newly mine) —
It's emforth, which, it's said, means "according to".

limerick_list.author: stella
limerick_list.text:
When I come for a cervical smear
I take the same tack every year.
With my legs open wide,
I go all glassy-eyed,
And simply pretend I'm not here.

limerick_list.author: Giorgio Coniglio
limerick_list.text:
Vincent moved there and painted because
He was nursing some grave mental flaws.
He surprised Doc Gachet —
A new canvas each day,
As the wizard of Auvers-sur-Oise.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
If you ball up a paper and throw it
You're littering; surely you know it.
If you ball up a mission
You're in the position
Of bungling the job, and you blow it.

limerick_list.author: Celia Warren
limerick_list.text:
He's a barrel of laughs, is our Rich —
Gives each aspect of life his best pitch:
Witty words, tossed in place,
Or a look on his face,
Will be sure to make someone's mouth twitch.

limerick_list.author: Chaiwallah
limerick_list.text:
Though charming in many ways, Kate
Seems to live in a permanent state
Of confusion, not knowing,
"Am I coming or going?"
That's why she's called "Kate addle-pate."

limerick_list.author: Chris Doyle
limerick_list.text:
Though it's spicy and hot and I worry
That, after I eat it, I'll hurry
Away to the loo
As it passes on through
Into poo, still I do favor curry.

limerick_list.author: Bit
limerick_list.text:
We've set up the ropes and the wires,
And the cross-bars and aerial fires!
You'll be thrilled!  You'll be scared!
So you'd best be prepared
For our aerobats: brave trapeze flyers!

limerick_list.author: rusty
limerick_list.text:
The scene of this sad song balladic
Is my great great great aunty's back paddock,
Where, as told in this verse,
The old bag lost her purse.
(It's called "Who in the Hell Stole my Haddock?")

limerick_list.author: Richard English
limerick_list.text:
An agama's a land-dwelling lizard
With a typically bright-coloured gizzard.
It's this reptile's salvation
To change pigmentation
To white if it's caught in a blizzard.

limerick_list.author: Kevin
limerick_list.text:
A cream pitcher's useful for serving
Of cream, and its lip may be curving.
It can also be straight.
If it's dropped on the plate,
The mess this creates is unnerving.

limerick_list.author: mrsrev
limerick_list.text:
You've been sent here while you convalesce
From your stroke—we will help ease your stress.
As you work your weak arm
We will keep you from harm,
And we pray you will quickly progress.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
As I stepped through the door, spirits soaring,
I expected the joint to be roaring.
I was sure I would score
With two dames, maybe more,
But the party was dullsville—just boring!

limerick_list.author: SusanL
limerick_list.text:
You know Hoops? He's concurrently dating
Both Peggy and Marge; he's debating
Which one he will take
For a cruise on the lake.
Soon he's gonna get caught—we're just waiting.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
The depositors using this bank
Are convinced it deserves its high rank,
But reports they'll receive
(And will hardly believe):
Their accounts all read zip—in the tank!

limerick_list.author: Peter Meyer
limerick_list.text:
The sound faded out by and by,
'Cause the batteries failed. Mum would cry,
Since the radio show
On Madame Mirabeau
Was now lost to her ears—how awry!

limerick_list.author: J. E. Pettit
limerick_list.text:
When the priest tells his people, "You shan't
Wear your clothing too sheer or too scant,"
He should look in the mirror:
His clothes are much sheerer,
And now it's much clearer: it's cant.

limerick_list.author: Mark Mironer
limerick_list.text:
You're cocksure, presumptuous, slick.
You think you're the best, but you're thick.
You are so immature—
It's not that that's "for sure",
But a rooster that grew from a chick.

limerick_list.author: mike scholtes
limerick_list.text:
Find a synthesis; that's my objective.
Conformers aren't fully elective:
Only one is desired.
A reaction's required
That's atropo-enantioselective.

limerick_list.author: Val
limerick_list.text:
Often shared at the end of the day,
Sweet endearments are words lovers say
To dispel any fear,
And to make very clear
Each is happy to stay, and not stray.

limerick_list.author: AndrewB
limerick_list.text:
Made from paper all coated with blue
(Or fake vellum and Mylar worked, too),
They held copied designs
That were shown with white lines.
They were blueprints, each showing one view.

limerick_list.author: Chris Young
limerick_list.text:
When my wife took her car for inspection,
It lacked rotors to aid speed-correction
(Pads engage when you tread).
"I need disc brakes," she said.
So I smashed up her record collection.

limerick_list.author: Val
limerick_list.text:
To command high respect, hold your place
With great dignity, calmness and grace
(While those watching may sense
Ermine robes leave you tense
And you're struggling to keep a straight face).

limerick_list.author: PGS and Jesse Frankovich
limerick_list.text:
The critical density? It's
The mass (or the number) that fits
In a specified space,
As the singular case
Of the critical state just permits.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
A pirate who's good with his scimitar
Can crucify foes without limit or
Induce the battalions
That guard Spanish galleons
To clear the entire perimeter.

limerick_list.author: Kevin Lucas
limerick_list.text:
As kids, we were close.  I must say,
Though, your politics drove me away.
I'm repulsed by your views.
Let's hang out?  I refuse.
But I'll go to your funeral, okay?

limerick_list.author: turnip
limerick_list.text:
The poor beanie, a small brimless cap,
Has acquired a rather bum rap.
It was worn by the frosh
In the old days, by gosh.
To remove one would cause quite a flap.

limerick_list.author: Janet McConnaughey
limerick_list.text:
My goat ranch has sure hit the skids.
Though my futures brought glittering bids,
My stock guarantee
Hit a goat STD —
An abortion storm cost me the kids.

limerick_list.author: Snowy Owl
limerick_list.text:
Her clothing has always been trashy;
Her hair, which was blonde, is now ashy.
Her locks have gone grey,
And her figure astray,
But at least her Rolls-Royce is still flashy!

limerick_list.author: Dr. Alphabet
limerick_list.text:
To Eliot, April is cruel.
As far as months go, he's a fool:
October's a curse,
November's a hearse,
And December's a harsh icy ghoul.

limerick_list.author: Jonathan Caws-Elwitt
limerick_list.text:
If your desk is equipped with a blotter,
You won't damage it when you spill water.
This paper's so handy!
You'll find it just dandy
For tracing your favorite pet otter.

limerick_list.author: SheilaB
limerick_list.text:
My talents were never gymnastic,
As my left foot's deformed; it's dysplastic.
With a custom-made shoe
I can walk good as you,
But do backflips? The strain would be drastic.
